<HEAD>Heavy Snow In The Central Appalachians</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Tennessee plane crash,
traffic deaths in Virginia; picks up 4th graf pvs: ``There's just .
..</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Heavy snow fell on the central Appalachians during the morning Friday, and high wind blowing out of the desert over southern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> fanned brush fires that destroyed homes. Up to 10 inches of snow fell in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, over the Mountain State's southern mountains and over the coal fields near the <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> border. Up to 10 inches also fell across the mountains of southwestern <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, a twin-engine airplane carrying 40 pounds of cocaine and $ 7,000 cash crashed into a snowy field outside <LOCATION> Knoxville </LOCATION>, killing its pilot and its sole passenger. Police said the cocaine was valued at $ 450,000. Authorities said heavy wet snow was falling and the ceiling was down to 400 feet at the time of the crash that killed pilot <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Chestnut </PERSON>, 47, of <LOCATION> Trotwood </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>; and <PERSON> Jeffery </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON>, 23, of <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>, officials said. The plane was en route from <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> Dayton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, with a fuel stop in <LOCATION> Knoxville </LOCATION> when it apparently lost an engine, said <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Barker </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. At least three traffic deaths in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> were blamed on slippery roads. Numerous schools were closed in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> and power was out to thousands of customers in the state's <LOCATION> Pulaski </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Radford </PERSON> and <PERSON> Giles </PERSON> counties. `` There's just no way we can count the number of accidents without polling each trooper and seeing how many he investigated,'' said <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> state police Sgt. G.A. <PERSON> Farthing </PERSON>. `` I'd be hesitant to even give a number.'' <PERSON> Rob </PERSON> <PERSON> Yates </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Shenandoah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, said the Skyline Drive near <LOCATION> Winchester </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, was closed because of heavy snowfall, and some visitors were stranded at visitor centers along the drive. Advisories warned of a chance of snow elsewhere in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, eastern <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>'s Eastern Panhandle. Squalls produced locally heavy snow around the lower <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> and heavy snow warnings were issued for northeastern <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and for the eastern <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION> counties of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> state. Light snow fell around the southern shore of <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> and over <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>. A storm slowly tracking across northern <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> threatened to produce heavy snow over parts of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. A winter storm watch was posted into Saturday for the state's central highlands, south-central mountains, and east-central and southeastern plains. A snow advisory was issued for parts of western <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Strong, gusty <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ana </LOCATION> wind continued to blow across southern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> for a third day with gusts to 60 mph reported at <LOCATION> Rialto </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Laguna </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peak </LOCATION>. More than 20 homes were damaged, some of them destroyed, northwest of downtown <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and thousands of people were evacuated. Elsewhere, showers were scattered from northern <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> across the <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> coast, with light rain and drizzle over the northern <LOCATION> Rockies </LOCATION>. Afternoon temperatures remained below freezing from northeastern <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> through the Great Lakes region and much of the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> to the northern <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>. Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from zero degrees at International Falls, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, to 83 at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Myers </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>. Friday morning's official low was 22 degrees below zero at <LOCATION> Hibbing </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>. For Saturday, snow was forecast from the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> region and the northern half of the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> to northern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> Rain was forecast from southeastern <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> through the <LOCATION> southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> and the lower <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> to southern <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and northern and central <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. Snow also was forecast over parts of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and northwestern <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Scattered showers were forecast from the coast of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> and western <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>, with snow at higher elevations. Highs only in the teens or single digits were predicted from the Dakotas through the Great Lakes to northern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>; in the 20s in the rest of the region from eastern <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> through the upper half of the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> to the northern <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>; above 50 from coastal <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> to the southern <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> and from the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> coast to southern <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>; above 60 from the central coast of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> to southwestern <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>; in the 60s and 70s across the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>; and in the 70s in southwestern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>.
