<HEAD>Labor Party Votes to Reopen Talks with Likud Bloc</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAMAT GAN, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s left-leaning <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> voted by an overwhelming majority Thursday to re-enter negotiations with the hard-line <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> bloc on forming a joint national unity government. The decision was a reversal of the party's 110-member Executive Bureau, which last week voted against further talks. It also was seen as a boost to the leadership of Foreign Minister <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peres </PERSON>, who pushed hard for a vote in favor of new negotiations. `` If this were not the vote, people would say it was a personal defeat, so I suppose it's a personal triumph,'' <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> told reporters after the results were announced. The vote of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> was 637 to 348. Just under 1,000 of the committee's more than 1,300 members attended the session in this <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION> suburb. Both <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> and the party's No. 2 man, Defense Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON>, made emotional pleas in favor of reopening talks with <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION>. They pledged, however, that they would agree to join a coalition government only if it would advance the peace process and was committed to reforming the electoral system. `` For 11 years the <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> has been in power,'' <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> told the committee. `` Almost all that is dear to us has been affected. What should we do? Be proud and go home, or try to find a solution and change the system?'' He added, virtually screaming into the microphone: `` I did not come to arrange negotiations, but to examine our souls.'' Likud first came to power in 1977, and <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> and Labor have governed <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> in an uneasy coalition since inconclusive elections in 1984. Israeli elections Nov. 1 again ended indecisively, with <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> winning 40 seats to <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION>'s 39. The remaining 41 seats were divided among smaller parties. Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> has been asked to form a new government and needs the support of Labor or several of the smaller parties to achieve a majority in the 120-seat parliament, or Knesset. Intense bargaining has been going on since the election. On Thursday, talks were held between <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> leaders and the <ORGANIZATION> Tehiya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, a nationalist party with three seats in the new parliament, and a tentative agreement was signed that would give a <ORGANIZATION> Tehiya </ORGANIZATION> member the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> portfolio, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> television reported. <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> officials also met with three other small parties, but no agreements were reached, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio said.
