<HEAD>Convicted Killer At A Loss Over Governor's Decision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANGOLA, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Despite the urging of parole officials, Governor <PERSON> Buddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> has refused to grant clemency to <PERSON> Wilbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Rideau </PERSON>, a convicted murderer who became a nationally recognized prison editor. `` I wish somebody would tell me what to do, and I'd do it,'' <PERSON> Rideau </PERSON> said in a telephone interview Thursday, a day after <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> rejected the state <ORGANIZATION> Pardon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>'s recommendation for a reduction of sentence. <PERSON> Rideau </PERSON>, 47, is serving life in the state prison for a 1961 <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Charles </LOCATION> bank robbery during which he kidnapped three employees, shot and wounded two of them and killed the third by cutting her throat. <PERSON> Rideau </PERSON> was arrested shortly afterwards and confessed in front of television cameras. He spent 10 years on death row until the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> struck down the state's capital punishment law in 1972. The board's second recommendation of reduced sentence would have made <PERSON> Rideau </PERSON> eligible for parole. In rejecting it, <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> cited the strenuous objections of <PERSON> Rideau </PERSON>'s prosecutors and victims. <PERSON> Rideau </PERSON>, who has won numerous national prizes as editor of the prison news magazine The Angolite, said he thinks he was turned down because his success with the magazine has kept him in the limelight. `` We've got a system that encourages anonymity. It encourages prisoners to do nothing, not to distinguish themselves,'' he said. `` If you want to get out of prison, you're supposed to keep your mouth shut and let everybody forget about you,'' he said. <PERSON> Rideau </PERSON> said he is not sure what to do next. Since the pardon board agreed with him, it would add nothing to get another hearing. <PERSON> Rideau </PERSON> said he can only hope that <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> will change his mind. `` I would love to meet the man,'' <PERSON> Rideau </PERSON> said. `` I wish I could sit down with him. Anything he wants to know, let me present my side.'' Although serving life, <PERSON> Rideau </PERSON> is frequently on the road, traveling under guard to lecture at state universities, appear on national television shows and cover state board meetings for the magazine. He and other editors have been singled out for national recognition by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, private foundations and other organizations.
