<HEAD>Jerry Lee Lewis Has Little Left, Lawyer Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rock' n' roller <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, facing a $ 2 million tax debt and other bills, has few personal possessions he could use to pay off creditors, a bankruptcy lawyer says. `` There's not much left,'' <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Hagemeyer </PERSON>, an attorney representing <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> in federal <ORGANIZATION> Bankruptcy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> here, said Thursday. <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, 53, filed for bankruptcy Nov. 8, citing debts of more than $ 3 million and income of about $ 5,000 a month, <ORGANIZATION> Hagemeyer </ORGANIZATION> said. The <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> has been squabbling with <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> since 1975, and tax agents have seized cars, furniture and other property from him several times over the years. `` There have been at least two sales by the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> that I know of,'' <ORGANIZATION> Hagemeyer </ORGANIZATION> said. <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>' bankruptcy petition lists a residence valued at $ 30,000 near <LOCATION> Nesbit </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, and other personal property worth about $ 6,000. In a hearing Wednesday, <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> said the income from an upcoming movie based on his life would fall well short of his debts. Responding to inquiries from bankruptcy trustee <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Emerson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> said a contract he signed eight years ago puts his income from the movie at $ 200,000 to $ 250,000. <PERSON> Emerson </PERSON> asked if <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> expected to perform any consulting work or other moneymaking activities for the producers of `` Great Balls of Fire'' starring <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Quaid </PERSON>. `` No sir,'' <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> said. `` I've suggested some things. We do n't see eye to eye on some things They're pretty well set on what they want to do.'' The movie about <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>' tumultuous personal life and the early years of his rock' n' roll career is being shot in <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>. In is petition, <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> listed 22 creditors, but his major debts are to the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> concert promoter who sued in 1978 after the rocker failed to show up for a scheduled performance, <ORGANIZATION> Hagemeyer </ORGANIZATION> said. <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> failed to show up to oppose the lawsuit and a judgment was filed against him for more than $ 450,000. With interest, he now owes about $ 950,000, the attorney said. <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> went to trial on tax evasion charges in 1984, but was acquitted of charges he intentionally hid money from the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION>. At the time, the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> said he owed the government more than $ 650,000. The singer's income comes primarily from performances, said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Bingham </PERSON>, an attorney representing <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> on matters other than the bankruptcy petition. <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, who recorded such early rock' n' roll classics as `` Whole <PERSON> Lotta </PERSON> <PERSON> Shakin </PERSON>' Going On'' and `` Great Balls of Fire,'' told the bankruptcy trustee he has not received any record royalties in the last few years.
