<HEAD>Chinook Accidents in Recent Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Honduras-US Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Here is a list of some accidents in recent years involving the twin-rotor <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> CH-47 Chinook helicopter. _ Feb. 25, 1988, an Army CH-47D crashed in a cow pasture near <LOCATION> Chico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, killing 10 soldiers and seriously burning eight. _ Nov. 20, 1987, an Army CH-47 crashed and burned in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, injuring two soldiers. _ May 15, 1987, an Army CH-47 caught fire and made a forced landing in dense woods near <LOCATION> Monticello </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ark. </LOCATION>, killing one soldier and injuring three. _ Feb. 27, 1987, a <ORGANIZATION> Chinook </ORGANIZATION> helicopter belonging to the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> crashed near <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Stanley </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Falkland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>, killing all seven aboard. _ Nov. 6, 1986, a Chinook 234, a civilian version of the helicopter, crashed in the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>, killing 45 people. The company that operated the helicopter said gearbox fatigue probably caused the crash. _ May 13, 1986, a <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chinook </ORGANIZATION> crashed into a mountain on <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falkland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, killing three crewmen. Officials said visibility was poor at the time. _ April 9, 1986, an Army CH-47D collided with an AH-1S Cobra helicopter over <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Stewart </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, killing eight soldiers. _ July 11, 1985, a CH-47D being tested before delivery to the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> crashed in a marshy area in southern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, killing two crew members. _ April 21, 1985, a CH-47D taxiing on the groun