<FIRST>r a PM-HolidayGrieving     12-09 0590</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Holiday Grieving,0617</SECOND>
<HEAD>Holidays Are Tough Times To Deal With Loss Of Child</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Holiday chimes may sound a somber note for families grieving over the loss of a child, but a psychiatrist suggests survivors start new traditions in memory of the departed. `` Families in mourning have to be told it is all right to have fun,'' says <PERSON> Abby </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wasserman </PERSON>, writing in the December issue of American Journal of Diseases of Children. `` Laughter is the best medicine for helping the bereaved cope with their loss. Having a good time does not mean that the parents loved their child any less,'' she said. `` In fact, they may be showing more love because by enjoying themselves, they are bringing their family closer together.'' In getting through the holidays, families must decide what is comfortable, Ms. <PERSON> Wasserman </PERSON> said. `` Changes can make things less painful,'' she said. `` A different tree with different decorations. Opening the presents at a different time. A different menu for dinner.'' Some families put a small Christmas tree on the child's grave, Ms. <PERSON> Wasserman </PERSON> said. Others light a candle or order special plants or flowers. Accompanying her article are some `` do's'' and `` do n't's'' for those spending time with bereaved parents during the holidays. Do: _ Talk about special qualities of the child they have lost. _ Allow them to express as much grief as they are feeling. _ Reassure them that they did everything they could. _ Pay attention to surviving siblings. But do n't: _ Say you know how they feel unless you have lost a child. _ Say the parents should be over the loss. _ Change the subject when they mention their dead child. _ Say they can always have other children. _ Point out that at least they have other children. Ms. <PERSON> Wasserman </PERSON>, a child psychiatrist at <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, says religion can be a source of comfort, but she cautions that surviving children might misinterpret some explanations. In one case, she said, the behavior of a 4-year-old boy was poor after his brother's death. `` When asked about this behavior change for the worse, he replied that he was not going to be so good that <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> would want him. This child had been told that his brother was so wonderful that <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> wanted him to live with him in heaven,'' Ms. <PERSON> Wasserman </PERSON> said. The Compassionate Friends, an international organization dedicated to helping parents overcome the loss of a child, recently sent out holiday suggestions to its 600 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> chapters. `` Sometimes the toughest part of all is the anticipation,'' said <PERSON> Therese </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodrich </PERSON>, director of group's national office in suburban <LOCATION> Oak </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brook </LOCATION>. `` You turn on the television and people are telling you to get the shopping done. It's all around us,'' she said in a telephone interview Thursday. `` Some people like to buy a gift that their child would have liked, and then give it to the <ORGANIZATION> Salvation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> or a church group.'' Other suggestions include urging families to change their holiday routines, mention the loss of their children in Christmas cards and discuss them when they feel comfortable with the subject. Mrs. <PERSON> Goodrich </PERSON>, whose 14-year-old daughter was killed by a car in 1971, says the first holiday without a child is the hardest. `` When a child dies, our priorities get shook up. We want to show a little more love,'' she said. `` I think people just need to be gentle with themselves. That's the main thing.''
</TEXT>
