Europe </LOCATION>. `` The path remains open and the pace of peace continues,'' the president said. Asked whether he believed <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> was transforming the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> into a less threatening nation, he replied, `` Yes, I do.'' He said <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s hasty return home, prompted by the devastating earthquake in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, was `` a sad final note to what has been an otherwise successful _ and I use the next words advisedly _ happy and historic visit to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' Asked to assess <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s long-term chances for political survival, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said: `` Well, I realize, and I think we all should, that he is battling a bureaucracy, because whether it's a <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> bureaucracy or one of our own, the first rule of bureaucracy is protect the bureaucracy.'' `` And it would mean some great changes for some of the `` Nomenklatura,'' as they call their bureaucracy there, if he institutes the reforms that he's talking about,'' he continued. `` But, on the plus side for him, it's very evident that the people of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> are on his side. And I have to believe that the Nomenklatura is going to have to think twice with regard to how far they would go in trying to block him when the man in the street over there wants the things that have been seen.'' __ greater than EDITOR'S NOTE: <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> covers the White House for The Associated Press
