<TEXT>
 Reflecting on the peaks and valleys of his presidency, <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said his toughest burden has been sending young Americans into battle and laboring to win the release of others held hostage. At two different points in his nationally broadcast news conference Thursday night, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> talked of difficult moments in the Oval Office. Asked what task he had found most difficult, the president quickly cited the sending of troops into combat. Saying that `` I think I am prouder of them than of anything that has happened'' during his nearly eight years in office, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> added: `` I do n't think there's anything tougher than to have to order these magnificent young men and women in our military ... into danger.'' `` That's got to be something that any president would hesitate on and have to say was the greatest burden,'' he said. At another point, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> cited the continuing captivity of nine Americans held by pro-Iranian elements in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, saying it was `` one of those things ... you go to bed with every night.'' During <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s presidency, more than 200 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military personnel were killed during a bombing of a Marine barracks in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, several thousand troops were sent into combat during the invasion of <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION>, in which 19 American soldiers were killed, and 37 crewmen aboard the USS Stark were killed in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> when their ship was struck by missiles fired by an Iraqi fighter. When asked what he most enjoyed about the presidency, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> replied that `` there are a number of things to miss.'' But <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said `` let me simply say one I enjoyed the most is the economic recovery.'' `` When I came here, for almost half a century, the debate on the