<SECOND>BC-Opera,0584</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attractive New `Aida' At Met</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will stand for PMs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An attractive new production of `` Aida'' at the Metropolitan Opera avoids the visual silliness of the two productions that arrived before it. This one makes dramatic use of the stage elevator to change sets. The opening night of the new `` Aida,'' a Met Opera Guild benefit, was tastefully conducted by <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Levine </PERSON> and gloriously sung by <PERSON> Leona </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> as <PERSON> Aida </PERSON>, <PERSON> Placido </PERSON> <PERSON> Domingo </PERSON> as Radames, <PERSON> Fiorenza </PERSON> <PERSON> Cossotto </PERSON> as <PERSON> Amneris </PERSON>, <PERSON> Sherrill </PERSON> <PERSON> Milnes </PERSON> as <PERSON> Aida </PERSON>'s father, <PERSON> Amonasro </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Plishka </PERSON> as the high priest. <PERSON> Domingo </PERSON> sounded sterling throughout. He surprised this listener by taking the optional lower ending, not the high C, at the end of `` Celeste Aida.'' Miss <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, singing her first <PERSON> Aida </PERSON> at the Met, bloomed into full vocal glory in the third act. She had longing in her voice in `` O patria mia'' and some beautiful pianissimos. Her voice has matured marvelously and still has youthful freshness. In many operas, the love music is in the first act, before things start to go wrong. In `` Aida'' the love music is in Act 4, after things have gone so wrong that <PERSON> Aida </PERSON> and Radames are sealed in a vault to die. Their duet was so beautiful that the audience did n't immediately break the spell with huge applause at the end of it Miss Cossotto, who made her Met debut as <PERSON> Amneris </PERSON> in 1968, is a fine musician, using her voice to brilliant advantage. Her stage personality, while not flamboyant, is striking, placing <PERSON> Amneris </PERSON>' royal but hopeless love for Radames in the foreground in the first two acts Miss <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>'s more retiring demeanor put Aida in the background. <PERSON> Milnes </PERSON> was in brilliant voice and form. Amonasro may be a captive but he's full of vitality and vibrant with plans. <PERSON> Plishka </PERSON> sang with admirable authority. The costumes, by <PERSON> Dada </PERSON> <PERSON> Saligeri </PERSON>, were mostly white trimmed with gold. <PERSON> Domingo </PERSON> began, a hero, in all gold, and ended, disgraced, in a dark striped tunic. Some scenes were played near the front of the stage, in front of a wall with huge bas reliefs of two seated Egyptians. Then this would lift for a scene using more of the stage. The most dramatic theatrical stroke is having Amneris' room in Act 2 sink out of sight. First, soldiers are seen standing on top of the set that's descending, then a platform for the king and <PERSON> Amneris </PERSON> is revealed, then all the citizenry _ now joined at ground level by the soldiers _ wait for the triumphal entry scene. In the final scene, the elevator is used again, so the audience sees <PERSON> Aida </PERSON> and Radames in the vault and Amneris in a temple above them. There is no silly dance in Act 1 while Radames receives his armor and no fight to the death during the triumphal entry scene. There is a dance there, by choreographer <PERSON> Rodney </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, making his Met debut, but it is n't silly. <PERSON> Gianni </PERSON> <PERSON> Quaranta </PERSON>, who is Italian and won an Academy Award in 1987 for art direction for `` A Room with a View,'' designed the sets. <PERSON> Sonja </PERSON> <PERSON> Frisell </PERSON>, a native of <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> who was on the staff of <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Scala </LOCATION> for 15 years, did stage direction. Both, making Met debuts, proved to be stars of the show.
