<FIRST>r w PM-AirForceSafety     12-09 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Air Force Safety,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>A-10 Warplane Has One of Best Safety Records In Air Force Fleet</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Germany Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warplane that crashed into an apartment building in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, killing four people, has one of the best safety records in the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> inventory. The A-10 Thunderbolt II is an older model ground-attack plane designed to be highly maneuverable at low speeds and low altitude and to carry a lot of bombs and ammunition. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> said the crash was the 14th serious, so-called Class A accident since Oct. 1, when the current fiscal year began, although it was the first involving an A-10. At the same point in the last fiscal year, the service had experienced nine Class A accidents. Among the 14 accidents recorded since Oct. 1 have been two involving the new B-1B bomber; one involving a B-52 bomber, and one involving an F-16 fighter in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> last Monday that killed the general in charge of <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> personnel in the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> says it is impossible to predict what type of safety record it will post for the year based on little more than one month's passage. During fiscal 1988, for example, the service experienced a grim record for its F-16 jet fighter, and yet finished the year by posting one of its best overall safety records in history. `` Nonetheless, it is true that our mishap rate has suddenly spiked up and we do n't know why,'' said one <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> official who asked not to be identified. `` We continue to examine our training procedures, maintenance and everything else.'' Wednesday's crash involved an A-10 on a training flight that inexplicably slammed into an apartment building in <LOCATION> Remscheid </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, killing at least four people, injuring dozens of others and destroying homes for more than a block. The A-10 is designed to support soldiers on the ground by attacking enemy tanks and other high-priority targets. The Thunderbolt first flew in 1975 and became operational with the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> in 1977. The plane is no longer in production, but the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> has more than 700 of them in its inventory. Statistically, the A-10 over time has been the safest fighter or attack plane currently in the inventory. The aircraft has chalked up a major accident rate of less than 4 Class A mishaps per 100,000 flying hours over its lifetime _ which now consists of more than 1.75 million flight hours. A Class A mishap is one in which there is either a fatality or damage exceeding $ 500,000 to an aircraft. In the fiscal year ended Sept. 30, the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> lost three A-10's, for a mishap rate of 1.37 per 100,000 flight hours. By comparison, the A-7 had a mishap rate of 6.04 per 100,000 flight hours; the F-16 a rate of 6.80 per 100,000 flight hours, and the B-52 a rate of 2.04 per 100,000 flight hours. The overall <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> rate for the last fiscal year was 1.63 serious mishaps per 100,000 flying hours _ representing 55 total accidents _ just slightly worse than the service's all-time best of 1.53 set in fiscal 1986. The surge in <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> accidents over the past month comes at a time when the other military services continue to report stable rates. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, for example, which enjoyed its safest year ever in fiscal 1988, is on track toward an even safer year. Since Oct. 1, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> has experienced only four Class A accidents. It recorded 37 in all of fiscal 1988, or more than three per month on average.
