<FIRST>r w PM-CorporateTaxes     12-09 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Corporate Taxes,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey: Tax Changes Taking Bigger Corporate Bite</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new survey shows that overhaul of the federal income tax is increasing the bite on corporations _ which is just what <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> intended. One thousand corporations surveyed by Tax Analysts paid about $ 7 billion more into the federal treasury last year than they did in 1986, when the tax laws underwent major revisions. The 1,000 companies, spread out among 49 industries, paid an average of 24.72 percent of their earnings in federal income tax in 1987, the study found. That compares with 21.54 percent in 1986 and 20.94 percent the previous year. Three out of four corporations paid a higher rate last year than the year before. While a portion of the increase is due to higher earnings in 1987, most is attributable to the new tax law, said Tax Analysts, a Virginia-based research and publishing organization. `` Tax reform is working,'' said <PERSON> Forrest </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marovelli </PERSON> of Tax Analysts. `` More corporations are paying higher taxes. Fewer are avoiding taxes.'' A major goal of the 1986 tax overhaul was to shift a greater portion of the tax burden from individuals to corporations. Over five years, the total shift is expected to be about $ 125 billion. The most significant corporate changes enacted were repeal of the special treatment of capital gains, toughening of the alternative minimum tax, repeal of the investment tax credit and restructuring of depreciation allowances. The general corporate tax rate was cut, from 46 percent to 33 percent, which benefited all companies. However, because different types of corporations took advantage of different provisions under the old tax law, there are significant variations in how they are faring under the new law, said <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Starcher </PERSON> of Tax Analysts. For example, a reduction in long-term accounting provisions more than doubled the average tax rate paid by aerospace companies, from 15.6 percent of earnings to 36.7 percent, the study found. On the other hand, apparel and furniture companies are paying generally lower taxes because they have the lower tax rates but lost relatively little in the other tax changes. According to the Tax Analysts calculations, the automobile industry paid the lowest tax rate last year _ a negative 6.93 percent _ while construction was highest at 58.9 percent. Both situations were exaggerated by special circumstancs, <PERSON> Marovelli </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the largest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> automaker, had a one-time tax writeoff that made the entire industry's situation look worse than it was; without <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Marovelli </PERSON> said, the industry would have paid 17 percent. The high rate on the construction industry reflected the same accounting changes that affected the aerospace industry, as well as a curtailment in use of installment sales, which in the past had produced a tax savings for that industry. Other industry figures from 1987 included: insurance, 14 percent; paper, 19 percent; drugs, 22.1 percent; banking, 23.6 percent; railroads, 23.9 percent; petroleum refining, 24.9 percent; lumber, 29.2 percent; textiles, 29.4 percent; services, 31.7 percent; tobacco, 33.1 percent; apparel, 34.9 percent; commercial printing, 35 percent; newspapers, 36.7 percent; and retail groceries, 37.1 percent. Tax Analysts bases its calculations on corporate filings with the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. Citizens for <ORGANIZATION> Tax </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION>, a labor-financed tax research group, reached similar conclusions in a study of profitable corporations released in September. That study concluded the number of profitable companies that paid no federal tax was cut by more than half last year _ to 16 _ and that the 250 companies surveyed paid an average of 22.1 percent.
