<HEAD>President Says US Eventually Must Negotiate With Iran On Hostages</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Reagan Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> says the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> eventually will have to negotiate with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> to gain the release of American hostages held in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, but insisted the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government would not consider paying any kind of ransom. `` We're looking at every channel that we can find to try and get them, and I imagine that the ultimate is going to have to be somehow a negotiation with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, because they have control of those people,'' he told a news conference Thursday. `` We are hopeful that there can be avenues that would open'' for the release of the hostages, he said. `` We can not enter into negotiating in the sense of what kind of ransom to pay, or you are just encouraging more hostage-taking.'' And in perhaps his last White House news conference, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> repeated that he did not believe his administration was bargaining with terrorists when it entered into the Iran-Contra affair. `` We were not negotiating with them in the so-called Iran-Contra affair at all. We were heeding a plea from some individuals ... And these people were among those who were planning ahead to have a government'' after the death of <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>. <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> remains the spiritual head of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said he would be willing to negotiate with <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>, with which <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> has had no formal diplomatic ties since the 1979-81 hostage crisis. `` There are conditions that have to be met also there. Anytime that they are ready to come forward on an open basis, we would be ready to talk to them,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>, speaking to reporters immediately after the news confere