<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 The writer traveled to <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> to cover the visit of Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, which was canceled.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAVANA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At a small park near the seashore, <PERSON> Ofelia </PERSON> <PERSON> Espinosa </PERSON> says sales at her newsstand of Soviet magazines were negligible two years ago. Now, she says, she prepares for a stampede whenever certain Soviet publications translated into Spanish arrive, particularly the monthly `` Sputnik'' and the weekly `` News of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>.'' The difference between now and two years ago is `` glasnost,'' President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s experiment with allowing open debate on issues once rarely discussed outside <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> walls. Glasnost has helped boost sales for Ms. <PERSON> Espinosa </PERSON>. She says she gets about 60 copies each of the two magazines per delivery. `` They're gone in about five minutes,'' she says, recalling the time not long ago when the same publications were discarded for lack of buyers. Today was to have been the day <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> began a three-day visit to <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, offering an opportunity to measure his appeal among ordinary Cubans. But he cut short his three-nation trip Thursday and rushed back to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> to supervise relief efforts in earthquake-stricken <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. For Cubans who sense that Marxism is here to stay but who are eager for a more flexible system, the Soviet leader is the most promising development in years. Several Cubans privately confess their admiration for <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. They hope for Soviet-style reforms in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, where outspokenness is discouraged and the economy has stagnated for years. However, millions of other Cubans appear to have retained their allegiance to <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>, who has made no secret of his disdain for <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms. He has left the impression that he is worried the system in place for 70 years in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> could unravel under <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s leadership <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> has insisted <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> will never accept any reform that `` reeks of capitalism.'' His inflexible stand has led to speculation about a possibly serious Soviet-Cuban rift. Despite the tension, <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> authorities had planned for <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> the grandest reception ever staged for a visiting luminary, with a projected 500,000 lining the parade route. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Cuban analysts agree that the foundation of Soviet-Cuban friendship remains solid. <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> helps the Soviets collect political support worldwide, and the Soviets lavish an estimated $ 5 billion in annual economic aid on <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>. Some Westerners, however, believe the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has been dissatisfied with <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> economic performance for years. It is not known if <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has pressured <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> to impose capitalist-style reforms to revive the Cuban economy. With the postponement of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s visit, the answer probably will not be forthcoming for now.
