nd $ 803.9 million, ending the year with a loss of $ 24.6 million. He based his projections on current payment patterns. `` The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> has yet to leave behind the spectre of the financial crisis. Throughout 1988, the organization has confronted the possibility of imminent bankruptcy, which it has narrowly managed to avoid so far,'' <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> wrote in the report. Only 79 of the 159 member states had paid all their dues as of Nov. 30, he said. `` Of the 80 member states still in arrears, 40 owed more than their 1988 assessments,'' he added. Assuming next year's payment patterns are like 1988, the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> chief said `` the organization would manage to avoid insolvency, but only by once again utilizing its reserves to meet cash requirements at many points during the year.'' The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> has a contingency reserve fund of about $ 210 million that must be replenished as soon as new dues are paid. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> often dips into this fund to start new peacekeeping operations or to meet operating costs. `` The financial situation of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> could rapidly and dramatically deteriorate should any additional demands be placed upon these depleted reserves to meet the cash requirements for existing or new peacekeeping operations,'' the report says. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said in September that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would gradually repay all its dues. It has withheld money in recent years to protest what the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration saw as mismanagement, overstaffing, and an anti-Western bias at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION>