<HEAD>Armenian Earthquake May Have Destroyed Priceless Art Treasures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The earthquake that devastated several cities and wiped out villages in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> may have also doomed priceless medieval art and early Christian churches in the region, an art historian said. `` That area is full of medieval monuments and churches,'' said <PERSON> Lucy </PERSON> <PERSON> Der </PERSON> <PERSON> Manuelian </PERSON>, professor of Armenian art and architecture at <ORGANIZATION> Tufts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` Some are over a thousand years old.'' Wednesday's earthquake destroyed two-thirds of <LOCATION> Leninakan </LOCATION>, a city of 250,000 people 30 miles from the epicenter, and wiped out the nearby village of <LOCATION> Spitak </LOCATION>, a Soviet TV correspondent said. Early estimates put the death toll at 50,000 to 70,000. Atop a mountain less than a mile from <LOCATION> Leninakan </LOCATION> is a 7th century church called St. Stepanos, which contains rare wall paintings. A domed church made of rose and brown-colored volcanic stone, <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Stepanos </LOCATION> is a `` priceless treasure,'' <PERSON> Manuelian </PERSON> said. She fears it may have been destroyed becaues it is so close to the quake's center, but she said she has not been able to find out. Also within a few miles of <LOCATION> Leninakan </LOCATION> is an 11th century Marmashen church and a 13th century monastery called <PERSON> Harich </PERSON>, which has a museum that may contain priceless medieval gospel manuscripts, <PERSON> Manuelian </PERSON> said. Across the border from <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> are the ruins of the 9th century capital city of <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, called <PERSON> Ani </PERSON>. Scholars believe that city's 10th century cathedral may have been the inspiration for Romanesque and Gothic architecture in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, she said. <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> was the first country to make Christianity its official religion in the year 314, <PERSON> Manuelian </PERSON> said. Its early stone churches are of special interest because some scholars believe that Europeans learned the building techniques used on their towering cathedrals from the Armenians. `` The Soviets have been spending million of rubles to restore these Armenian churches,'' <PERSON> Manuelian </PERSON> said. `` Whatever is destroyed of medieval Armenian architecture is a terrific loss, because the ones in <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> are n't being taken care of.''
