<HEAD>Dollar Falls Against Yen, Stocks Up Moderately</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar fell against the Japanese yen today in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, while stock prices rose moderately as participants weighed the impact of the resignation of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s finance minister. The dollar ended the week at 122.43 yen, down 0.59 yen from Thursday's closing of 123.02 yen. After opening sharply lower at 122.20 yen, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency edged up, ranging between 122.10 and 122.47 yen during the day. The dollar's decline in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> followed a drop in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, where it closed Thursday at 122.28 yen. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, many participants began selling the dollar after Finance Minister <PERSON> Kiichi </PERSON> <PERSON> Miyazawa </PERSON> announced his resignation, said <PERSON> Mitsuhiko </PERSON> <PERSON> Kinugasa </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Daiwa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. Many traders feared the departure of <PERSON> Miyazawa </PERSON>, who had opposed a weaker dollar, could damage current international monetary coordination, he said. <PERSON> Miyazawa </PERSON> announced his resignation near midday, saying he wished to clear the way for the passage of tax reform bills now being discussed in the upper house of parliament. Opposition parties had opposed a continuation of debate on the bills until <PERSON> Miyazawa </PERSON> resigned because of inconsistencies in his accounts of his involvement in a stock trading scandal. Dozens of politicians and other influential people have been linked to the scandal, involving the purchase of unlisted shares in <LOCATION> Recruit-Cosmos </LOCATION>, a real-estate company, at bargain prices, and their subsequent resale when the stock began being traded publicly. Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> accepted <PERSON> Miyazawa </PERSON>'s resignation and appointed himself finance minister. He told reporters today that <PERSON> Miyazawa </PERSON>'s departure from the Cabinet would not have a strong impact on exchange markets. On the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which plunged 291.92 points Thursday, regained 34.52 points or 0.11 percent, closing the week at 29,793.42. Many traders stayed on the sidelines because of caution over the possible impact of <PERSON> Miyazawa </PERSON>'s resignation on the currency and stock markets, dealers said. <PERSON> Toshiaki </PERSON> <PERSON> Yui </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> said the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> rose in spite of the wait-and-see mood because of lingering bullishness from the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> index having achieved the 30,000-point level for the first time on Wednesday and the rise of the dollar after the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s announcement of an arms reduction. `` Minor stocks have been attracting participants recently, which is likely to help the market accumulate strength,'' he said. <PERSON> Yui </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> index has been strong because the Japanese economy is expanding, whereas the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> continues to run large trade and budget deficits. Volume traded on the market's first section was estimated at 1 billion shares.
