<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-Soldiers     12-09 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Soldiers,0667</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Weapons Deter Crowds, Help Soldiers Feel More In Control</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JEBALIYA, Occupied Gaza Strip (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A year after the Palestinian uprising began, <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> soldiers believe they are gradually regaining control of the streets despite ongoing clashes. Talks with soldiers in both the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> indicate morale is much improved since the chaotic early days of the uprising, when thousands of <LOCATION> Palestinians </LOCATION> joined demonstrations against <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s 21-year occupation. Today, the best evidence things have changed is that confrontations are usually limited to skirmishes with small groups of <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> youths who appear only long enough to hurl a stone before vanishing into the narrow alleyways. `` In the beginning we used to face crowds of 5,000 people. Now we are dealing with at most about 100,'' said Lt. Col. <PERSON> Micha </PERSON>, whose infantry unit recently returned to this squalid refugee camp of 70,000. <PERSON> Micha </PERSON> recalls that in December 1987 his unit was transferred from <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> and thrust into the riots without training or the necessary tools. `` We got here and we suddenly had no weapons to use, no artillery, no tanks,'' said <PERSON> Micha </PERSON>, whose full name was not disclosed in keeping with army policy. `` We had clubs, and they had sticks, and we battled like gangs. Officers were simply told to make the situation quiet, and there was a lot of gray in the orders so every soldier had his own method for dealing with the population.'' At least 320 Palestinians have been killed in the rebellion since it began Dec. 8, 1987, in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. Eleven Israelis also have been slain and 7,000 Palestinians wounded during the same period. In recent interviews, army commanders attributed the drop in large protests to improved crowd control devices such as plastic bullets, which are less lethal than live ammunition and allow soldiers to use rifles more freely. The army also has developed fender-mounted tear-gas launchers, rooftop guns that fire rubber bullets, hot marbles or gravel, and a wagon equipped with a scoop to remove roadblocks. `` Soldiers feel they have an answer. There is no longer such frustration and feelings of impotence. The soldiers feel they control the situation,'' said Col. <PERSON> Segev </PERSON>, who commands troops in <LOCATION> Nablus </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>'s largest town. Taunted by demonstrators who hurled provocative insults as well as stones and bottles, soldiers sometimes lost control, beating detainees or smashing houses and cars. In one case last spring in <LOCATION> Kfar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salem </LOCATION> village, soldiers used a bulldozer to bury alive four Palestinians. The four were rescued by witnesses minutes later. The army said 45 soldiers have been court-martialed since last December for using excessive force. More soldiers have been disciplined through less formal trials. The army will not say how many. Brig. Gen. <PERSON> Ehud </PERSON> <PERSON> Gross </PERSON>, the chief army education officer, described the number of violations as `` minor'' when compared to the thousands of soldiers who have been sent to the occupied areas. Israeli newspapers say the army has an average of 10,000 troops deployed each day in the occupied territories _ several times the pre-uprising level. In an interview, <PERSON> Gross </PERSON> emphasized repeatedly that the army believed excessive force would have a boomerang effect. `` If we want to bring some tranquility, some peace to the area, the less we create polarization and hatred by revenge the more chances there are for better future understanding,'' he said. The new emphasis on restraint is contained in a two-day course instituted recently to prepare soldiers for duty in the occupied areas and in a new briefing kit prepared for commanders. Gross said the army's mission was to restore enough order to `` enable the government to make its decisions free from pressure, or under the least amount of pressure possible.'' He claimed the army `` can cope with the mission, and we can fulfill it.''
</TEXT>
