<TEXT>
 The abrupt departure of <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> elicited sympathy and sadness from those who were dropped from his itinerary, but others fed up with two days of `` Gorby-lock'' had few regrets. `` The mood is very sad,'' said <PERSON> Elaine </PERSON> <PERSON> Fink </PERSON>, principal of P.S. 6, the <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> grammar school that had hoped to host the Soviet leader's wife, <PERSON> Raisa </PERSON>, Thursday afternoon. `` It's a lesson in disappointment for us all.'' The lesson was echoed at each planned stop by the <ORGANIZATION> Gorbachevs </ORGANIZATION> on their final day in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>. The Soviet leader returned home a day early to lead relief efforts for victims of a massive earthquake that ravaged <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. `` I think the only thing we can say is to express sympathy for the earthquake victims,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON>, head of public relations at the Metropolitan Museum of Art, another Big Apple tourist sight missed by <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. The Soviet President's admiring <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> hosts managed to squeeze in one last event just before he boarded his plane at <LOCATION> Kennedy </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> just after noon Thursday. Former astronaut <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Irwin </PERSON> presented <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> with a Soviet flag that went to the moon in 1971 with the Apollo 15 mission. <PERSON> Irwin </PERSON> said he and his crewmates, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> and <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Worden </PERSON>, signed the flag, which was one of a number of foreign flags carried by the moonwalkers. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and his wife also had planned a short stroll through Central Park before their museum visit and a morning stop at the Javits Conve