<HEAD>Soviet Quake Coverage Unprecedented, Aimed At Healing Ethnic Rift</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet-Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With Pravda headlining `` Our pain and tragedy'' on its front page and television showing soldiers digging for schoolchildren in piles of rubble, Soviet media have covered the devastating earthquake in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> with unprecedented detail and urgency. `` Helpless, sobbing people are climbing on the wreckage of an apartment house, from which can be heard heart-rending cries for help,'' Pravda reported today in a dramatic departure from its typical dry reports of Communist Party decrees and speeches. `` Powerless, without anything they can do, the living superstitiously run back and forth,'' the story said. Driven by destruction that has killed tens of thousands of people, Soviet authorities are using the media to broadcast urgent appeals for everything from heavy-duty cranes to blood. Officials also are emphasizing the need for national cooperation in coping with the tragedy, in an attempt to use the disaster to stop the ethnic strife that has killed at least 60 people in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> and neighboring <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> this year and sent 180,000 fleeing their homes in fear of mobs. Parts of both republics were being patrolled by soldiers and tanks when the quake hit. `` Reproaches and mutual offenses are thrown away'' in the aftermath of such a tragedy, Azerbaijani health minister T.A. <PERSON> Kasumov </PERSON> said on national television Thursday. `` There is a saying among the <LOCATION> Azerbaijani </LOCATION> people: ` The pain unites,''' he said. `` Our hospitals are ready to take patients and wounded from <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, and they will be surrounded by special care and attention,'' <PERSON> Kasumov </PERSON> promised. That would be a stark contrast to recent weeks, when medical care and food supplies had been denied to whole neighborhoods of Armenians in <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>. The focus of much of the Soviet reporting has been on the rescuers rather than victims. Television journalists spoke sadly of tens of thousands of dead Thursday, but their film showed crunched and crushed buildings rather than children's mangled bodies. Reporters interviewed officials about the rescue effort instead of grieving parents. Broadcasters spoke of half the city of <LOCATION> Kirovakan </LOCATION> being leveled, but they showed no aerial photos indicating the extent of the damage. Nor were there pictures of tent cities being erected to shelter families left homeless by the quake. Most Soviet photographers aimed their cameras at the relief effort: evacuation of victims by military helicopters, cranes clearing away destruction and volunteers rushing to donate blood. A few of the photographs published in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and sent abroad by the official news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> show grieving women in <LOCATION> Spitak </LOCATION>, and mothers and their bundled children huddling around campfires in the remnants of downtown <LOCATION> Leninakan </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> photographer <PERSON> Sergei </PERSON> <PERSON> Chistyakov </PERSON> said his agency sold one such dramatic photo to the French photo agency <ORGANIZATION> SIPA </ORGANIZATION> for $ 2,500 for its exclusive use outside the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` I hate to sell pictures of the tragedy,'' he said. `` But we are on ` self-accounting' now, and they say we must.'' Soviet enterprises are switching to a new economic regime where they must turn a profit. Today's reports in the national newspapers were the first to detail the suffering of the victims. The story was given remarkable prominence. Pravda ran a photo of a partially collapsed building on its front page, a spot normally reserved for pictures of happy workers and politicians. The relative speed of the coverage is also remarkable in a nation that until recently ignored natural disasters. Just last week, it left unreported the hijacking of a bus full of 30 schoolchildren until foreign news agencies learned of it through air traffic control communications on the hijackers' plans to fly to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. The earthquake was first reported in one of the most unlikely sources of news on the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Iran </ORGANIZATION>. But shortly thereafter, Soviet seismologists confirmed it to questioning reporters. Still, it was not until eight hours after the quake hit that <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> called it a disaster. And it was not until Thursday, when President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> cut short his trip to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> to oversee relief efforts, that officials began to speak of thousands of dead. Part of the delay can be explained by the destruction itself. <PERSON> Chistyakov </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> photographers based in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> reached the damaged area via military helicopter while the <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> correspondents were stuck on the blocked highway. As a result, he said, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> had pictures ready to transmit before it had a story.
