<DATELINE>PINE MOUNTAIN, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hansels and Gretels beware: <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Brochu </PERSON>'s gingerbread house may be the world's largest. <PERSON> Brochu </PERSON>, executive chef at the <ORGANIZATION> Callaway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gardens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inn </ORGANIZATION>, had the help of seven chefs, 13 cooks and the entire maintenance department of the west <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> resort to build the gingerbread house _ complete with lights, chimney, picket fence lined with poinsettias and icicles hanging from the roof. There are 450 pounds of candies and cookies in the decorations. Modeled after the structure that almost led to the downfall of Hansel and <PERSON> Gretel </PERSON> in the fairy tale, the house on display in the lobby of Callaway Gardens through New Year's Day. The structure, 14 feet long, 6 -LCB- feet high and 4 feet wide, is built from, among other things, 1,200 pounds of powdered sugar, 175 sheet pans of gingerbread, 1,080 egg whites, 120 pounds of honey, 550 pounds of all-purpose flour and 1,200 assorted Christmas lights. `` It might be a record, we do n't know,'' <PERSON> Brochu </PERSON> said. `` But it's just beautiful, especially at night with all the lights. Working night and day for three days over Thanksgiving weekend, it took <PERSON> Brochu </PERSON> and his crew 315 hours to complete the confectionary castle.
