<HEAD>Sakharov Ends U.S. Trip, Heads To Paris</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bidding goodbye after a four-week visit, Soviet human rights activist <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> called the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> a wonderful country but said he had no desire to move here. `` I think that my fate is completely bound up with the country where I was born, and I want to live there,'' <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> said Thursday night before boarding a jet to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> and a possible meeting with Polish Solidarity leader <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>. The 67-year-old Nobel laureate also called for an international effort to aid victims of the massive earthquake that struck <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, killing tens of thousands of people. <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> arrived in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> Nov. 4 as a Soviet delegate to the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Survival </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Humanity </ORGANIZATION>, an organization formed this year by Soviet and American scientists to foster cooperation on arms control, hunger, pollution and other issues. During his stay, he visited relatives in the <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> area, attended a private dinner in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and met with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. He also underwent tests at <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> <LOCATION> General </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, where doctors determined he did not need a heart pacemaker. It was <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>'s first visit to the West, and he and others hailed it as a symbol of change in the <LOCATION> Sovie