ditional.'' He warned that perestroika still faces many obstacles and that the reforms `` can not yet be called irreversible.'' He praised <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s announcement Wednesday of unilateral troop cuts, saying the Soviet leader `` has taken a very important initiative ... that will broaden international support for him and therefore strengthen his position in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>, who received the Nobel Peace Prize in 1975 for his human rights activities, plans to attend a celebration in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> of the 40th anniversary of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Universal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Declaration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION>. He said he may also meet with <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> before returning to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>.
