<FIRST>r a PM-CDC-CancerDeaths     12-09 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-CDC-Cancer Deaths,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cancer Remains No. 2 Cause Of Premature Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Cancer rates are declining, but the disease remains the second leading cause of premature death in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>. In 1985, the last year for which statistics were available, cancer accounted for the loss of 1.95 million years of `` potential life'' Americans would have had if they had lived to age 65, the Atlanta-based <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday in its weekly report. Only injuries, with a loss of 2.2 million years, ranked higher. The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> counts `` years of potential life lost'' to various causes as a way of measuring premature mortality, using age 65 as a statistical benchmark. The actual life expectancy is higher. Since 1968, the mortality rate from cancer for Americans under 55 has dropped significantly, from 43 deaths per 100,000 people in that age group in 1968 to 35 in 1985. Over that same time, the annual rate of potential life years lost has fallen as well, from 1,074 years lost among every 100,000 people to 926. `` All of that leads to some guarded optimism _ that cancer rates in younger people are, in fact, declining,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Rothenberg </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> cancer specialist. In the 1985 figures, the highest rate for potential-life years lost to cancer was among black males, at 1,208 years per 100,000 such people. Following were white males, 949; black females, 877; and white females, 841. But while proportionately fewer people are dying early of cancer, the population is growing _ particularly `` baby boomers,'' now ages 24-42. Thus, cancer's toll in the total number of `` years of potential life lost'' has remained virtually constant for two decades, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> noted. `` Understanding the basis and public health implications of this decline -LRB- in cancer death rates -RRB- requires further investigation,'' the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said, noting that such efforts should include study of cancer incidence and survival among younger Americans. Additionally, <PERSON> Rothenberg </PERSON> said, researchers have another concern: With improvements in other areas of medicine, such as treatment of cardiovascular disease, Americans are living longer, so the cancer rate for people over 65 is increasing. `` It sounds simplistic, but it means they're living long enough to get cancer,'' he said.
</TEXT>
