<HEAD>Treaty Inspectors Celebrate INF's First Birthday,</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet and <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> officials ate rum cake with frosting missiles in a party marking the first anniversary of the signing of the Intermediate Nuclear Forces treaty. `` Do n't let anybody carry that cake outside,'' one partygoer said Wednesday, joking about <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>'s liquor laws. `` We could get busted.'' In the Soviet city of <LOCATION> Votkinsk </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> inspectors suspended the policy prohibiting alcohol after their Soviet escorts brought in pastries and wine. Americans are in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to verify that the Soviets no longer produce SS-20 missiles at the Votkinsk Machine Building Plant. The Soviets are here to make sure no more Pershing II missiles are built at the Hercules Aerospace plant in <LOCATION> Magna </LOCATION>. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> signed the INF Treaty in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on Dec. 7, 1987. The agreement, which bans medium-range nuclear missiles, took effect in June. <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> and Votkinsk are the only two permanent inspection sites named in the treaty. `` What we're doing today is starting a joint cultural tradition, with the celebration of the signing of the treaty that brings you here to <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Szatkowski </PERSON>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> site commander, said during the party. As many as 30 Soviet inspectors will serve two - and three-month duty tours for the next 13 years in <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> under terms of the treaty `` There's certainly a sense of history in what we're about here and a sense of pioneering in the area of peace,'' <PERSON> Szatkowski </PERSON> said. `` I think we're all proud to be a part of this exciting time in international history.''
