<HEAD>Fatal Beating At Church Camp Described</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OREGON CITY, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An 8-year-old girl was beaten as many as 500 times, slammed against a wall and dropped on the pavement the night she died at a church camp, one of four people accused in the death told authorities. The girl, <PERSON> Dayna </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorea </PERSON> <PERSON> Broussard </PERSON>, hid in a corner but the beatings continued with a hose after a plastic pipe and bamboo cane broke, <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Doolittle </PERSON>, 28, told a deputy sheriff. The girl was the daughter of <PERSON> Eldridge </PERSON> <PERSON> Broussard </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, founder of the <ORGANIZATION> Ecclesia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Athletic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> that ran the camp at a rural house southeast of <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Broussard </PERSON> also ran the <ORGANIZATION> Watts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. A tape of an interview <PERSON> Doolittle </PERSON> gave to the deputy the day after the girl's Oct. 14 death was played Thursday before <LOCATION> Clackamas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Circuit Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON>, who is considering pre-trial defense motions to suppress information the defendants provided authorities. Charged with manslaughter in the girl's death are <PERSON> Doolittle </PERSON>, <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brinson </PERSON>, 30, <PERSON> Constance </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, 37, and <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Chambers </PERSON>, 35. Defense lawyers allege in their motion to suppress the information that the defendants were not properly advised of their rights. <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON> made no decision and said the hearing would continue Monday. The judge said he was delaying the start of the defendants' trial until Feb. 6. <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON> also released <PERSON> Doolittle </PERSON> and <PERSON> Brinson </PERSON> on their own recognizance. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and Chambers were released in mid-November. On the tape, <PERSON> Doolittle </PERSON> told how he came to <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> a few days before the child's death to work at the camp. When he arrived, <PERSON> Doolittle </PERSON> said <PERSON> Chambers </PERSON> told him <PERSON> Dayna </PERSON> had been a problem and they would have to discipline her. He said <PERSON> Chambers </PERSON> told him the child had stolen some pieces of chicken she was not supposed to have. <PERSON> Doolittle </PERSON> said the beating began Oct. 13 when <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> pushed the girl against a wall three to five times, after which the girl said she was having trouble seeing and was dizzy. <PERSON> Doolittle </PERSON> said he and <PERSON> Brinson </PERSON> held the girl down while <PERSON> Chambers </PERSON> beat her repeatedly with a leather strap, a bamboo cane and a plastic pipe. Some 250 to 500 blows were delivered, <PERSON> Doolittle </PERSON> said. He said the girl also was taken outside and dropped on the pavement three to five times. At one point she tried to run and hide in a corner. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> then beat her with three extension cords braided together. Authorities said the beating lasted about 90 minutes. The child later was taken to a fire station, where a firefighter tried to administer first aid. After the girl's death, the state took custody of 53 children living at the camp. Officials said the children were systematically beaten.
