<HEAD>Pope Condemns Terrorists Who Claim To Speak For Minorities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> urged today that the rights of minorities be respected, but he also condemned any recourse to violence to advance their claims and lashed out at terrorist groups acting in their name. `` May those who follow the inhuman path of terrorism hear my voice: to strike blindly, kill innocent people or carry out bloody reprisals does not help a just evaluation of the claims advanced by the minorites for whom they claim to act,'' the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> said in his message for the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>'s World Day of Peace. The message, sent to world leaders each year, was titled `` To Build Peace, Respect Minorities.'' <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> officials said the message was in general terms and that <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> had no specific ethnic, racial, religious or national group in mind, although his words seemed directed at a number of situations in the world. The pope acknowledged that `` delicate problems arise'' when a group seeks independence or greater political autonomy. `` I wish to state that, in such delicate circumstances, dialogue and negotiation are the obligatory path to peace,'' he said, adding that a refusal to enter into dialogue `` can open the door to violence.'' He also declared that states that perpetrate or tolerate acts aimed at endangering the lives of minorities, violate `` the fundamental law governing the social order.'' In situations of real injustice, he said it may be the duty of groups which have emigrated to demand justice for oppressed in their homelands. But he called for care `` especially when it is difficult to have objective information.'' The church marks its World Day of Peace on Jan. 1 but the <PERSON> pope </PERSON>'s message is traditionally issued in advance
