<BYLINE>By MARJORIE ANDERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An inspection prompted by last year's fatal <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> subway fire found many weaknesses in fire safety precautions and emergency preparedness in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s subways. Eleven of the subway system's 48 escalators lack sprinklers, about one quarter of the token booths inspected have inadequate emergency communications equipment and about half the fire extinguishers that are supposed to be along the tracks are missing or empty, according to a report on the inspection released Thursday. The fire in the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> Underground, which killed 31 people, began when someone dropped a lighted match on a wooden escalator. The <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> subway system does not have wooden escalator treads. After the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> fire, the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> reactivated an old contract to install sprinklers at all 48 escalators at a cost of $ 5.7 million, but a month later called off the project because of budget concerns. The <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> subway system has not had a fire like the one at King's Cross Station in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, but it averages 5,000 blazes a year, mostly minor car and track fires caused by rubbish. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Reuter </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Transit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION>'s vice president for rapid transit, said that since the audit, his agency has made safety improvements and plans more. The audit found 11 of the subway system's escalators are not equipped with sprinklers and warned that inadequate cleaning allows flammable debris and grease to build up beneath them. There have been three escalator fires in the past five years, two in escalators without sprinklers. Both apparently were sparked by cigarettes, although smoking is illegal in the subway system. Since the audit, the <ORGANIZATION> Transit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> has intensified its escalator maintenance, <ORGANIZATION> Reuter </ORGANIZATION> said. The audit also found that of the 118 token booths checked, 28 had neither a working emergency communication system nor a substitute auxiliary phone. These systems are used to contact the <ORGANIZATION> Transit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> command center, which is responsible for calling the Fire Department. <ORGANIZATION> Reuter </ORGANIZATION> said an $ 11.8 million contract to replace the transit booth communications systems has been awarded. <ORGANIZATION> Transit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Gunn </PERSON> wrote in his response to the inspection that the authority is trying to deter thefts of fire extinguishers. `` Locking or otherwise securing extinguishers in the tunnels was deemed unacceptable,'' he said. `` Police stakeouts also are utilized. This situation is still being studied.''
