<HEAD>Orders Hearings On Beverly Hills Fire Claims Cases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES WOLFE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFORT, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Kentucky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> today ordered the state <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Claims </ORGANIZATION> to hold hearings on a group of claims filed against the state after the 1977 <ORGANIZATION> Beverly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hills </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> fire that killed 165 people. The board had dismissed the claims without notice in 1987, saying it had the `` inherent'' power to do so and that it would not have been liable to the claimants, anyway. But the appeals court said in a precedent-setting opinion that the board and similar administrative agencies, unlike courts, `` have no ` inherent' powers.'' `` The Board of Claims is entirely a creature of the legislature. ... There is no explicit grant of authority -LRB- in <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> law -RRB- giving the board the power to take on an adversarial role and dismiss claims'' on its own motion, the court said in a 2-1 ruling. The board was created by the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> to handle damage claims against state agencies, which under the <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> Constitution can not be sued for negligence. The fire on May 28, 1977, led to years of litigation against dozens of companies that manufactured materials used in the construction or furnishing of the club at <LOCATION> Southgate </LOCATION>, just across the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. In July 1985, <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> became the last of 14 defendants in a federal civil suit against aluminum wiring manufacturers to reach settlements totaling $ 14 million. Settlements by other defendants had totaled $ 30 million by 1984. The appeals court upheld <ORGANIZATION> Campbell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, which earlier had consolidated the claims by the estates of seven people into a single case and ordered it back to the board for hearing. The board appealed that ruling. Failure to give the claimants notice of dismissal or to allow them to respond with legal arguments was a violation of the constitutional guarantee of due legal process, the appellate panel said.
