<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two brothers led a gang that sold $ 100 million in cocaine a year and used violence to control the streets and drive off competing dealers, prosecutors said. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> `` Dread'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, 32, a Jamaican-born alien, was among 23 people named in a 72-count federal indictment unsealed Thursday. If convicted, he faces a maximum penalty of life imprisonment and a $ 108 million fine. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> has been in custody since August on charges that he killed one man and wounded another in a 1986 street shooting. His trial on those charges is set for January. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, his brother, <ORGANIZATION> Everton </ORGANIZATION>, 29, and other members of the gang routinely used violence to maintain control over those who sold the drugs, including crack, and to keep them from reporting their activities to police, said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Baylson </PERSON>. The defendants, 16 of whom were in custody this morning, were charged with violating federal drug, racketeering and firearms laws. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Leary </PERSON>, in charge of the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> office here, said the acts the defendants allegedly committed `` are tantamount to those of an urban terrorist group which has violently sought to satisfy its own greed by preying upon those addicted to illegal narcotics.'' `` They had little or no regard for anyone who stood in their way,'' <PERSON> Leary </PERSON> said. `` They have oppressed children into doing their bidding and have threatened the fabric of life in this community.'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>'s gang allegedly handled an annual average of 2,000 pounds of cocaine, plus an unknown quantity of marijuana, said <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Billbrough </PERSON>, who heads the <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> office of the <ORGANIZATION> federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. A pound of cocaine sells for about $ 11,000 wholesale, and the retail price is roughly five times that, making the gross sales more than $ 100 million yearly, <PERSON> Billbrough </PERSON> said. All the defendants are charged with conspiracy to manufacture cocaine base, commonly called crack, and to distribute cocaine, crack and marijuana. The Smiths and two others also are charged with engaging in a continuing criminal enterprise in violation of the federal `` drug kingpin'' law, which carries a maximum life sentence.
