<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHE CACHERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Solididarity leader <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> today made his first foreign trip since <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s martial-law crackdown seven years ago and told reporters it was time to leave the Stalinist system behind. `` After seven years, here I am at the dawn of something new,'' said a smiling <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> after his arrival at Charles de Gaulle airport. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, who was permitted to accept the invitation of President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> to join observances of the 40th anniversary of the <ORGANIZATION> Universal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Declaration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION>, said he was looking forward to meeting Soviet physicist <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>, another Nobel Peace Prize laureate invited by <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> to Saturday's ceremonies. `` We both still feel, he and I, the breath of <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> at our backs,'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said, speaking Polish through an interpreter. `` The Stalin era is over. Now I am waiting for the return to pluralism and the restoration of rights.'' Before leaving <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> told reporters, `` There are several elements which cause hope that everything's going to be better.'' But he said problems remained, such the government's monopoly on trade unions and its handling of social, political and economic problems. `` That is still the breath of <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>. It was not communism, it was him. And we have to end it ... by way of evolution and not revolution.'' `` I'd like to reach an agreement at last on pluralism and to finish the Stalinist system for good,'' he said. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> also was to confer with French trade unionists, the mayor of <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> and Cardinal <PERSON> Jean-Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Lustiger </PERSON>, leader of the French <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, before returning Monday. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, bundled in a thick coat and sporting a front-billed fur cap, received cheers of `` Bravo Lech!'' when he arrived at <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>'s central train station from <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION> earlier in the day Crowds also gathered around him and historian <PERSON> Bronislaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Geremek </PERSON> at the airport, with parents holding up children for a better view. <PERSON> Geremek </PERSON>, a senior Solidarity adviser, was accompanying <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> on the trip. In a departure from past practice, the state-controlled media treated <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> as a public figure instead of as a private citizen. His departure for <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> was listed by the official <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> news agency as one of its top stories of the day. It was the first time since the imposition of martial law in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> in December 1981 that <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> received permission to travel abroad. The issuance of a passport to him Monday coincided with increasingly positive treatment of <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> in the official press since he appeared in a nationwide television debate Nov. 30. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> was viewed by supporters as having handily won the debate with official unions' chief <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Miodowicz </PERSON>, and the non-confrontational tone of his remarks drew praise even from normally hostile government officials. The Solidarity leader last left <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> in October 1981, also to visit <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> has led Solidarity since the inception of the first independent trade union in the Soviet bloc in August 1980. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> had insisted <PERSON> Geremek </PERSON>, a French medieval scholar who speaks French fluently, accompany him. Also making the trip with <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> was <PERSON> Andrzej </PERSON> <PERSON> Wielowieyski </PERSON>, vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligentsia </ORGANIZATION>.
