<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-Trek     12-09 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Trek,0579</SECOND>
<HEAD>Right-Wing Groups Celebrate 150th Anniversary of Pioneer Trek</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 On horseback and ox-drawn wagons, Afrikaners paraded into the city Friday to celebrate the 150th anniversary of the white pioneers' trek into the country's heartland. The march, held seven days before the official anniversary, was organized by right-wing white groups. They object to the upcoming government-backed ceremony, which has been billed as open to all races. Nearly 1,000 whites, dressed in 19th century pioneer outfits, arrived in downtown <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION> to mark the Great Trek, the 1838 journey by Afrikaners away from the British-ruled <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Colony </LOCATION> into the country's uncharted interior. Altogether about 3,000 people attended the parade, with wagons arriving from several locations across the country. The Great Trek is the most momentous event in Afrikaner history. Stories about hardships on the journey and battles with African tribesmen have taken on mythical proportions for the Dutch-descended Afrikaners, who dominate the government. `` Today we remember how our ancestors built this country into a civilized area where it's safe for whites to live,'' said <PERSON> Dann </PERSON> <PERSON> Combrink </PERSON>, 62. <PERSON> Combrink </PERSON>, wearing a leather vest and wide-brimmed hat, was accompanied by his wife in a period costume that included a bonnet and a full-length lavender and white dress with lace trim. `` This a day Afrikaners should be together,'' said <PERSON> Combrink </PERSON>. Organizers said blacks were not welcome at Friday's ceremony or at an evening gathering at the Voortrekker Monument, a huge granite structure on a hill overlooking the capital. `` The Great Trek marked the coming of our oppression, the stripping of our rights,'' said a 45-year-old black man who asked to be identified only as <PERSON> George </PERSON>. `` When I see this, I am very angry, very bitter.'' The 100th anniversary commemoration, held in 1938, is regarded as the catalyst that united the Afrikaners and gave impetus to their political organizations. Ten years later, the Afrikaner-dominated <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> came to power and began codifying their apartheid policies of racial segregation. But the two separate trek celebrations illustrate the fracture between right-wing Afrikaners, who oppose all concessions to the country's black majority, and President's P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which calls for gradual race reforms and limited power-sharing. Friday's ceremony was organized by the Afrikaner Peoples' Guard, a right-wing cultural group. The contingent that received the loudest applause was from the neo-Nazi <ORGANIZATION> Afrikaner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resistance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION>, led by the charismatic <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> TerreBlanche </PERSON>. Most members of <PERSON> TerreBlanche </PERSON>'s group opted not for the 19th century attire of their ancestors, but wore khaki outfits with swastika-like emblems on the shoulders. <PERSON> TerreBlanche </PERSON> and his followers received sustained cheers as they rode around Church Square in the city center, in front of the courthouse where five black anti-apartheid leaders were sentenced to prison Thursday on treason and terrorism convictions following a controversial trial. The government-sponsored trek left <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION> on Aug. 27 for the 870-mile trip to <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION>. Despite the government's announced intention of opening the celebrations to all races, few non-whites have participated. The government functions will dominate the next week leading up to the Day of the Vow, a national holiday, on Dec. 16. On that day in 1838, the Afrikaners vowed to make the date forever holy if they defeated a hostile Zulu tribe. They did so in the Battle of <LOCATION> Blood </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, and the day remains the most revered in Afrikaner history.
</TEXT>
