accusations about its policies in <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> or its one-party state. `` It is no good to force one country's standards on another,'' Friday's <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> report said. `` Interference in a country's internal affairs on the pretext of human rights should be strictly forbidden.'' Western human rights groups have persisted in criticizing <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s record In February, the Washington-based group <ORGANIZATION> Asia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Watch </ORGANIZATION> said <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> authorities tortured <LOCATION> Tibetan </LOCATION> activists seeking independence from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and performed forced abortions on members of minority groups. Pro-independence Tibetans have rioted twice in the past two years, leaving dozens dead in <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION>, the region's capital. The Asia Watch report quoted one Tibetan as saying, `` if one speaks forcefully, if one gives an account of <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> as being independent, they apply cattle prods.'' Earlier this year, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> also criticized <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> for its actions in <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>. An <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> report in April accused <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> of denying prisoners access to lawyers or their families. In earlier years, the London-based group has called for the release of <PERSON> Wei </PERSON> <PERSON> Jingsheng </PERSON>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s most prominent dissident, who as a leading member of the `` Democracy Movement'' was jailed in 1979. Last week, one of <PERSON> Wei </PERSON>'s former associates, <PERSON> Ren </PERSON> <PERSON> Wanding </PERSON>, who spent four years in jail for his views, renewed his call for free elections in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ren </PERSON>, who was freed in 1983, also a