<FIRST>r w AM-ShuttleRockets     12-09 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shuttle Rockets,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Engineers Say Rockets Worked Properly on September Shuttle Flight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gas leaked past a caulked seal in the nozzle of a rocket booster used to launch space shuttle Discovery in September, but a <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> official said Friday that this was anticipated by the design and is `` a non-problem.'' <PERSON> Royce </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, manager of the booster program at the <ORGANIZATION> Marshall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, said in a telephone interview that an examination of the disassembled Discovery solid-fuel rockets showed the engines worked `` as expected'' and that the gas leakage has been seen in testing and is considered a normal event. `` We're very happy with these motors,'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said engineers examining the disassembled rocket parts found that gas seeped between panels of ablative material in the nozzle of one of the two boosters. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> official said the nozzles of the solid rocket boosters are lined with panels of ablative material that is designed to burn away during the firing of the rocket. This action keeps extreme heat from penetrating the interior of the rocket nozzle. Between the panels of ablative material, <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said, engineers designed in a small gap to allow for thermal expansion. `` As just one more little protection, we inject an RTV -LRB- room temperature vulcanizing -RRB- silicone in there,'' he said. `` From time to time, we get some gas past this thermal filler.'' But he said the rocket booster nozzle is designed to accommodate this gas leakage and that the leak seen on the Discovery rocket engines was not unexpected or damaging. Two O-ring seals are the primary protection against leak of the gas and neither of these seals showed that they had been touched by superheated gas or flame. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said that during full-scale tests of the rocket motor, an unfilled 10-inch gap was left between the ablative panels of the nozzle `` to demonstrate that we're tolerant'' to a leak through that gap. `` Not even the sheen was taken off the surface of the O rings,'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said of the test. The accident that destroyed Challenger, which blew up 73 seconds after liftoff from the Kennedy Space Center in January 1986, was blamed on the leak of gas or flame from a field joint of a solid rocket booster. Since then, the rocket engines have been redesigned and tested with full-scale firings. The Discovery launch in September, the first shuttle mission since Challenger, used the new rocket design. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said engineers are only now beginning to examine the engines used last week for the launch of space shuttle Atlantis, but that no problem has been found with those rockets. `` This is a good motor,'' he said. `` We're ready to fly again.'' The next shuttle flight is scheduled for January.
