<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An aging liberal bloc on the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, anchored by ailing Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, is prompting renewed speculation on the impact President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will have on the court's future. <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, hospitalized Thursday with pneumonia, was reported Friday to be improving at the <ORGANIZATION> Bethesda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. Court spokeswoman <PERSON> Toni </PERSON> <PERSON> House </PERSON> said he may miss little time on the bench since the high court begins a four-week recess Monday. <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, 82, is the court's oldest justice and senior member in terms of service. He is two years older than the court's two other most consistent liberals, Justices <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> and <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON>, both 80. Aside from <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>'s current bout with pneumonia, the three have appeared to be in good health and have given no signs they plan to step down anytime soon. Including Justice <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, 68, the average age of the court's liberal bloc is over 77. By contrast, the average age of the five more conservative members is slightly under 60. That group includes three appointees of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>: <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>, 58, named in 1981 as the first woman on the high court; and <PERSON> Antonin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON>, 52, and <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, 52, both named during <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s second term. In addition, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> elevated <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON>, 64, to chief justice to succeed <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Burger </PERSON>. The ninth justice, <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, 71, an appointee of President <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, votes more often with the conservatives on key issues. While <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>'s illness lends new drama to conjecture about the high court's future, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> may have a more immediate impact on the lower federal courts. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is expected to search out conservatives to fill the existing 41 federal court vacancies _ 32 trial judgeships and nine appeals court posts. There could be many more for the president to fill over the next four years. Observers doubt that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will be as devoted to conservative ideology as <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, who made 375 judicial appointments, filling more than half the total. Guessing <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s likely <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> appointees is a parlor game with conflicting clues. The president-elect has said he likes `` moderate people with conservative views.'' He also pledged during the campaign to pick judges `` who will interpret the Constitution, not legislate from the bench.'' `` I will appoint judges who do n't reserve all their sympathy for criminals, who understand that victims have rights, too,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. As further evidence of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s conservative leanings, he supported <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s unsuccessful attempt to place <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bork </PERSON> on the high court. <PERSON> Bork </PERSON>, opposed for his conservative ideology, was defeated last year in a bruising political battle in the Democratic-controlled <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. Associates of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> are quick to point out that the president-elect was a close friend of the late <PERSON> Potter </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON>, a moderate justice with much the same upper-class lineage. Asked if <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was likely to pick someone closer to <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> than <PERSON> Bork </PERSON> if there is a <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> vacancy, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> spokeswoman <PERSON> Sheila </PERSON> <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> declined to speculate. `` That's a pothole over which I will leap,'' she said. A Republican strategist who requested anonymity predicted <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` will not choose anyone who is anathema to the movement conservatives'' _ the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> ideologues who rallied around <PERSON> Bork </PERSON>. That strategy may rule out Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>, the former governor of <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> whose conservative credentials have been questioned. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> himself said in a recent interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> that `` judicial restraint'' is a qualification for the bench. He said he favors picking the best person available. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also has said he will not impose a litmus test on judicial appointees. Anti-abortions would like assurances that the next justice, if given the chance, will vote to overturn the high court's landmark <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> decision of 1973 that legalized abortion nationwide Legal experts offer a cross-section of names, including some moderates, when asked to speculate on likely <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> choices for the high court. The largest group consists of federal judges and includes the following <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> appointees to the bench: _ <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Higgonbotham </PERSON>, 49, an appeal