<TEXT>
 A senior <LOCATION> Mongolian </LOCATION> official on Friday welcomed Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s pledge to reduce Soviet troop strength in this Central Asian country and said the process already has begun. First Deputy Foreign Minister <PERSON> Daramyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Endon </PERSON> said all the Soviet troops could be pulled out if relations with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> continue to improve. `` We do n't think there is a need for foreign troops,'' <PERSON> Endon </PERSON> told a news conference. He said <LOCATION> Mongolia </LOCATION> and its close ally, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, had decided to cut a large portion of the Soviet garrison in <LOCATION> Mongolia </LOCATION> in order to strengthen mutual understanding and trust with other <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> countries, especially <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday he planned to reduce the Soviet army by nearly 10 percent and unilaterally reduce the Soviet troop presence in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mongolia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Endon </PERSON> refused to say how many Soviet troops will be withdrawn or by when. He said military experts have yet to make those decisions. `` I can only say that a large part of the Soviet troops will be withdrawn,'' he said. `` The process has already begun and will continue until the end.'' The presence of about 1 million Soviet troops along <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s border, including those inside <LOCATION> Mongolia </LOCATION>, has been one of the major obstacles to ending the nearly 30-year-old Chinese-Soviet rift Last year the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> withdrew one division containing about 12,000 troops from <LOCATION> Mongolia </LOCATION>, leaving about 50,000 by Western estimates. They are believed to be confronted by an equal number of Chinese soldiers on the opposite side of the 2,900-mile-long Chinese-Mongolian border. <PERSON> Endon </PERSON> praised recent improvements in <LOCATION> Chinese-Mongolian </LOCATION> relations that have accompanied the warming trend between <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. He said there has been much progress toward normalization of government and party relations. The two countries signed trade and consular agreements in 1986. He said <LOCATION> Mongolia </LOCATION>'s foreign minister will visit <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> next year for the first time since the Chinese-Soviet split. <PERSON> Endon </PERSON> noted that during the 1950s, when <LOCATION> Mongolia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> were on good terms, <LOCATION> Mongolia </LOCATION> did not station any troops along its border with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. He said <LOCATION> Mongolia </LOCATION> ideally would be able to cut its own military forces if relations with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> continue to improve. `` Instead of sending our young men to the army we could use them in the building of socialism,'' he said.
