<HEAD>Famed Montparnasse Restaurant Restored to 1920s Splendor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARILYN AUGUST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 La Coupole, the landmark <LOCATION> Left </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> restaurant where struggling young artists like <PERSON> Chagall </PERSON> and <PERSON> Picasso </PERSON> traded their paintings for hot meals, reopened Friday after eight months of renovations restoring its 1920s decor. `` La Coupole is more than a restaurant; it's an institution,'' said <PERSON> Jean-Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Bucher </PERSON>, <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Coupole </PERSON>'s new owner. <PERSON> Bucher </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Groupe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flo </ORGANIZATION> chain of brasseries known for good food, fair prices and quick service, said the Coupole `` machine'' still had to be oiled and would get off to a slow start so as not to disappoint regular customers. The menu still features house specialities like lamb curry, steak tartar and baked <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, and there are welcome additions from <PERSON> Flo </PERSON>'s nouvelle cuisine fare Prices have been held down, <PERSON> Bucher </PERSON> said, and the lamb curry, served with three tasty chutneys, can be had for $ 15. La Coupole has been a watering hole for artists and intellectuals, movie stars and politicians since it opened 61 years ago with <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Cocteau </PERSON>, <PERSON> Man </PERSON> <PERSON> Ray </PERSON>, <PERSON> Andre </PERSON> <PERSON> Derain </PERSON> and <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Aragon </PERSON> on hand for the champagne. A decade later, <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Hemingway </PERSON> and <PERSON> Willian </PERSON> <PERSON> Faulkner </PERSON> nursed double scotches there while <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Durrell </PERSON> played chess long into the night. The post-World War II generation of existentialists made La Couple their haunt. Until his death in 1980, <PERSON> Jean-Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Sartre </PERSON> lunched there daily with <PERSON> Simone </PERSON> <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Beauvoir </PERSON>. The Coupole's main dining room is a classified historical monument and renovations of its vintage 1920s decor cost an estimated $ 5 million. On hand for the inaugural lunch of foie gras, scallops, chicken fricasee and an orange mousse cake washed down with vintage <LOCATION> Medoc </LOCATION> wines was <PERSON> Rene </PERSON> <PERSON> Lafon </PERSON>, 91, the Coupole's original owner. `` Entering the restaurant I was very happy to find my Coupole,'' he said. The famed 32 pillars, wrapped with original, but mostly unsigned canvasses painted by artists from the School of <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> _ turned out to be a Pandora's box. Under the cracking plaster, workmen found a type of emerald green stone that looked like marble. Though it was once the rage of <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> and still adorns the facade of some of the city's loveliest buildings, repairs were no easy matter: this man-made stone is no longer manufactured. The paintings themselves had been darkened beyond recognition by 60 years of smoke and cooking grime. They are now more resplendent than ever, thanks to four well-positioned spotlights on each post. `` We can really see the enormous variety of styles and colors adopted by painters of the School of <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyse </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Castelbajac </PERSON>, head of the restoration team, told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. She said very few of the paintings are signed, and are thus a mystery that is unlikely ever to be solved. `` One painting has Picasso colors, but its forms are pure <PERSON> Modigliani </PERSON>, so it's hard to say for sure whose it is,'' she said. `` I guess that will always be part of La Coupole's charm.''
