<HEAD>Palestinians Say Revolt Will Go On</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JABALIYA, Occupied Gaza Strip (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Refugees in this camp where the Palestinian uprising began a year ago were shut inside their shacks under military curfew Friday, but they said jailings and economic hardship would n't halt their rebellion. `` We are preparing for a long struggle. Palestinians have reached a point of no return,'' said a medical official in Jabaliya, the largest and most militant camp in the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. Jabaliya's narrow dirt alleys were deserted Friday except for a few goats picking through garbage piles. The occasional roar of an army jeep was the only sound breaking the silence. A few residents peered from the windows of their cement and corrugated tin huts. On Dec. 9, 1987, the camp was the site of the first demonstration in what came to be known as the `` intefadeh,'' or uprising. About 1,000 Palestinians shouting `` Death to the Israelis'' and chanting Islamic slogans hurled stones at soldiers. Troops opened fire, killing 17-year-old <PERSON> Hatem </PERSON> <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Sisi </PERSON>. Since then, more than a dozen residents have been killed in clashes and more than 1,000 treated for gunshot and beating injuries. The camp's 60,000 refugees have been confined to their homes for 116 days in the past year, and money is tight. Most young men are in jail. `` The next generation has taken their place,'' said the medical official, speaking on condition of anonymity. `` The stone-throwers are now 13 and 14 years old.'' Palestinians throughout the occupied territories seem to have settled in for a long confrontation with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> while trying at the same time to maintain some normalcy. `` This has become our way of life,'' said a 24-year-old teacher for handicapped children who would only give his first name, <PERSON> Emad </PERSON>. Scores of members of his extended family were gathered in the lush backyard of his home in <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s middle-class <LOCATION> Rimal </LOCATION> district. In the past year, it has become a clan custom to meet during strikes and curfews to help pass the time, <PERSON> Emad </PERSON> said. The uprising has touched even the youngest, <PERSON> Emad </PERSON> said. He pointed to his nephew, <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON>, a 2-year-old with curly blond hair who was hiding shyly behind one of the adults. `` The first word he learned was soldier, not mother or father,'' <PERSON> Emad </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Emad </PERSON> said he had planned to get married on Saturday, but had to postpone the wedding because of Friday's indefinite curfew which confined the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>'s 650,000 residents to their homes. At <LOCATION> Ahli </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, a five-minute drive away, doctors had settled into their `` strike day'' routine. During strikes called by the PLO-backed underground leadership, the casualty toll usually rises, in part due to increased army raids. `` In the beginning, we were completely overwhelmed by the number of casualties,'' said a senior surgeon who refused to be further identified. He said 4,200 patients had been admitted in the past year, most with injuries sustained during the uprising. Now, all doctors are on duty on strike days. Elective surgery is postponed and patients with light injuries are sent home to free beds. On Friday, only few clashes were reported in <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION>, and by midday doctors had only treated four beating victims. In the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> refugee camp of <LOCATION> Balata </LOCATION>, four Palestinians were wounded after Moslem noon prayers, Arab hospital officials said. The relative calm was, in part, the result of the curfews and heavy army presence. Dozens of jeeps patrolled <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s streets, and foot patrols combed Jabaliya and the nearby Shati camp. The low level of violence also indicated that Palestinians are shifting their emphasis from street confrontations to nation-building as the uprising enters its second year. The <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> declared a Palestinian state during a Nov. 15 session in <LOCATION> Algiers </LOCATION>. As part of the effort, local popular committees run by pro-PLO activists organize anti-crime patrols, provide first aid, visit families of those killed and settle disputes. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> has outlawed the committees, but activists said the groups continue to function, taking the place of the old leadership of clan heads and and Israeli-appointed officials. `` We will have a state, but we do n't expect it quickly,'' said <PERSON> Sammy </PERSON>, 26, a top activist in the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> Shabiba </ORGANIZATION> youth movement of <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Fatah </ORGANIZATION> group. `` In the meantime, it's important to show we are a nation.
