<HEAD>League Wants U.N. Observer Membership For PLO</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> said Friday it will campaign to make the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> an observer-member of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, putting the organization on a level with <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>. `` We are now going to try and get a resolution that would make the Palestinian state an observer-member of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Clovis </PERSON> <PERSON> Maksoud </PERSON>, the league's <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> representative, said at a news conference. The session was called primarily to discuss next week's special <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> meeting in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> at which <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> will speak. <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> was denied a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> visa on grounds he has been involved in terrorism. The league, formed in 1945, comprises 21 <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> states and `` Palestine,'' which it says is represented by the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> is currently one of two groups with permanent observer missions to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, the other being the <ORGANIZATION> South-West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Africa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. The current status recognizes their claim to represent peoples. The new designation would rank the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> among `` non-member states,'' elevating the status of the Palestinian people in Israeli-occupied territory. <PERSON> Maksoud </PERSON> said there would be no point in trying to make the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> a full member, because it could not win approval by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. But, he added, `` Maybe this can be a transition to full membership at a later date.'' The non-member states are <ORGANIZATION> Monaco </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Marino </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>. Discussing the Israeli raid Friday at <LOCATION> Naameh </LOCATION>, 50 miles inside <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Maksoud </PERSON> called it a `` pre-emptive strike against the peace option'' and timed to coincide with the first anniversary of the start of uprisings in the Israeli-occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. `` This is a signal of further oppression yet to come,'' <PERSON> Maksoud </PERSON> said. `` This is unprovoked violence by <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. There has been no provocation. It is an attempt to destabilize <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> and to continue its illegal occupation of the south of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Maksoud </PERSON> criticized President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s comment at his news conference Thursday night that <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>'s statement Wednesday saying the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> accepts <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and rejects terrorism `` in all its forms'' was ambiguous. `` We consider that Mr. <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>'s statements have been clear, unequivocal and categorical,'' he said. `` There is n't any ambiguity.'' <PERSON> Maksoud </PERSON> said that `` to include the uprising within the context of terrorism, as the reaction of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> seems to include, is mind-boggling and unacceptable.''
