<HEAD>USA Today Employees Concerned About Miscarriages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Officials and employees of <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Today </ORGANIZATION> are concerned about an unusually high number of miscarriages among women working in its newsroom. Some employees at the newspaper's suburban <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> headquarters fear that a reported 14 miscarriages among 100 women employees over the past 15 months may be partially attributed to several months of construction work in the offices or to prolonged exposure to video terminals. Editor <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Prichard </PERSON> said Friday that the company is giving `` close attention'' to the matter. Senior Editor <PERSON> Wanda </PERSON> <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON>, who confirmed only that there have been `` some miscarriages,'' said: `` Certainly the company is concerned about anything to do with employees. I'm concerned. I'm very concerned. But she also said: `` This is an internal matter and a very personal matter for the women involved. We're still looking into it and we do n't really have any more to say.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> on Friday reported that 14 miscarriages had occurred among USA Today employees since September 1987. Scientists say about one in seven pregnancies ends in a miscarriage and that there have been studies of about a dozen cluster occurrences in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> since 1980. A common thread in the incidences was the use of video terminals in the offices, although no direct link has been made between their use and pregnancy problems. A <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Today </ORGANIZATION> reporter, who asked not to be identified, said the company brought in experts on video terminals to discuss any danger they might pose and has been taking an informal survey of employees to determine the extent of the problem. Management also has sent out a memo telling employees not to talk about the miscarriages, the employee said. `` The sheer magnitude of the construction work caused a lot of concern,'' the reporter said. `` Guys with jackhammers were breaking up walls right next to your head. You'd walk in to find your terminal covered with dust. And there were weird smells, very pungent odors. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilcox </PERSON>, an epidemiologist who has studied miscarraiges for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION>, said he had no personal knowledge of the <LOCATION> USA </LOCATION> Today cases but they appear to be significant enough to merit study. He said, however, it was possible the occurrences were only coincidence and it is likely no cause will ever be proved. Extensive epidemiological studies would be required to determine whether there was any common cause, he said, since a number of factors could have contributed to each case. The Post did not say how many staff members had been pregnant, but one employee said there were no successful pregnancies among women working on the two floors that have been undergoing rennovation since April. <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which owns the internationally distributed newspaper, recently hired a consultant to test materials being installed during renovation, the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> reported `` There's a lot of concern in the building about the construction, especially among women who have miscarried,'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, a general assignment reporter interviewed by the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>. He said the company appeared to be `` genuinely concerned'' about the problem. `` Everyone is real frightened,'' a women who had a miscarriage and who asked not to be identified, was quoted by the Post as saying. `` You do n't know what's going on. It's really an ordeal.''
