<SECOND>AM-Okeechobee Pollution,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>District Endorses Plan To Save Okeechobee, Delays Details</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A sweeping plan to stop the pollution of <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Okeechobee </LOCATION> was endorsed by water directors Friday, but they delayed adopting details of the regulatory program until February, pending more hearings. The plan envisions strict limits on farm runoff into the lake, limits that some farmers say could drive them out of business. The nine board members of the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> voted unamimously to approve a resolution supporting limits on the overall pollution content of the 700-square-mile lake, the nation's largest fresh-water lake outside of the Great Lakes system. The policy change comes in the wake of increasing phosphorus pollution over the last two decades that has spawned deadly algae blooms, wiping out fish and native plant species. One recent reading found phosphorus levels at a historic high in the nation's largest fresh-water lake outside of the Great Lakes system. Water from the lake flows into the <ORGANIZATION> Loxahatchee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Refuge </ORGANIZATION>, into Everglades National Park and to water-conservation areas that recharge the <LOCATION> Biscayne </LOCATION> aquifer, southeastern <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s primary water supply <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Finley </PERSON>, superintendent of <ORGANIZATION> Everglades </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION>, said that the plan could prevent the lake from becoming little more than a retaining pond for polluted water. `` But if it's finessed, delayed and circumvented, then it's going to be the year 2002, and the nutrient front -LRB- phosphorus -RRB- will still be a cancer moving south, and we will have lost more of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s resources,'' <PERSON> Finley </PERSON> said One factor prompting the toughened standards was a federal suit filed by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Dexter </PERSON> <PERSON> Lehtinen </PERSON> accusing the district and the state of failing to protect water quality in the interconnected water system of the lake, <LOCATION> Kissimmee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Everglades </LOCATION> <LOCATION> National </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lehtinen </PERSON> had said he might consider dropping the suit if the district adopted the new standards, but spokeswoman <PERSON> Diane </PERSON> <PERSON> Cossin </PERSON> said Friday that the office would wait until it could examine the final plan. The biggest potential losers in the battle over phosphorus pollution, which comes principally from fertilizer and cow manure, are the sugar cane growers and dairy farmers who surround the lake. <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Parsons </PERSON>, representative of the <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sugar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>, said the new rules may drive cane growers in a few areas out of business, although most would be able to survive the runoff limits. He complained about the direction of policy, however, saying its aim seemed to be to force growers and dairy farmers to retain their runoff on their property. `` If you say that to the city of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, the city of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> would n't exist. What are you going to do _ tear down the public library and build a retaining pond?'' <PERSON> Parsons </PERSON> said. Environmentalists, who support the district plan, said the situation can not be compared with city sewage disposal. `` This is a scarce resource,'' said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Podgor </PERSON> of Friends of The Everglades. `` You can not equate <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Okeechobee </LOCATION> to a trash dump.'' The district's pollution management plan would require all lakeside farms to decrease the phosphorus content of their runoff at least one-fifth by 1991, and they must meet interim goals before then. Some dairy farms would have to cut phosphorus levels by more than 80 percent. The district was required to submit a draft plan to the state by December under the state's Surface Water Improvement and Management Act.
