<HEAD>Brite &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 What is a Christmas display without a laser light show anyway?. Striving to outdo himself, <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Copeland </PERSON>, the owner of Popeyes Famous Fried Chicken, has added the light show and artifical snow to his gaudy annual holiday display _ the one the <ORGANIZATION> Louisiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> forced him to move away from his home in suburban <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>. Now at his corporate headquarters near a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> shopping center, the display featuring more than a million lights was to be lit up for the first time this season Friday. <PERSON> Copeland </PERSON> started his Christmas displays outside his suburban mansion in the early 1980s, but they grew to the point that thousands of people would jam the streets to gawk at the lights and giant figures of reindeer, <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Claus </LOCATION>, a snowman and angels. Unhappy neighbors went to court and, in 1985, the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ordered the display turned off and dismantled. <PERSON> Copeland </PERSON> moved the show to his corporate offices two years ago.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>IOWA CITY, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The `` binocap'' and shoestring holders beat out the doggie doorbell and flavored clarinet reeds in a 5th-grade battle of inventors. <PERSON> Jeremy </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Alberhasky </PERSON> said he hated holding binoculars during a football game so he invented the binocap, combination headwear and binoculars, by gluing snap-out pocket binoculars to a baseball cap. The 11-year-old was one of the winners at <ORGANIZATION> Regina </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>'s invention contest. <PERSON> Katie </PERSON> <PERSON> Drop </PERSON>, 10, also was a winner with shoelace holders made out of Velcro fasteners. `` Shoelaces always come undone and you trip on them,'' she said. `` I put Velcro on so they stay up.'' Everyday problems were on the minds of most of the young inventors. Tired of awful-tasting clarinet reeds, <PERSON> Lucy </PERSON> <PERSON> LePeau </PERSON>, 11, dipped some in peppermint and orange extract. <PERSON> Katie </PERSON> <PERSON> Lacina </PERSON>, 10, invented a doggie doorbell so she would not have to constantly check to see if her dog wanted to come inside. She tied a spring, bell and bone to a piece of string so her dog could announce its arrival by pulling on the bone.
