<FIRST>r a AM-LowRentRuling     12-09 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Low Rent Ruling,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Upholds Law Protecting Low-Income Housing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge, ruling in the nation's first case challenging the constitutionality of the Emergency Housing Preservation Act, upheld the law in an opinion favoring low-income tenants in a gentrifying neighborhood. Although other courts do not have to follow its example, the ruling could influence other challenges to the 1987 act, which was designed to protect rent-controlled, federally subsidized private housing for low - and moderate-income families, an attorney for the plaintiffs said Friday Attorney <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> called Thursday's ruling a victory for rent rights of the poor, who are threatened by an increasing number of young professionals moving into renovated inner-city neighborhoods. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Moran </PERSON> issued his ruling in a class-action lawsuit filed on behalf of 600 residents of a North Side building. The act prohibits private owners of federally subsidized housing from immediately charging higher, market prices for rent if the change would result in a reduction of available low - and moderate-income housing The case <PERSON> Moran </PERSON> ruled on involved owners of a 209-unit apartment building who sought to pay off a federally insured mortgage 20 years early. The partnership that owns the building, known as the 833 <ORGANIZATION> Buena </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Venture </ORGANIZATION>, gave the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> $ 1.8 million in January to pay off the mortgage and then sent eviction or rent-increase notices to the 600 residents, believing the paid-off mortgage had exempted them from the regulations. The owners maintained that the housing preservation law was unconstitutional and deprived them of their property without due process. And in any event, they said, they paid up before the president signed the bill on Feb. 5, <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> said. But <PERSON> Moran </PERSON> noted that the law clearly had a retroactive effective date of Nov. 1, 1987, and said <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> had made `` a conscious choice to ignore a legislative demand'' in accepting the prepayment, said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilen </PERSON>, another attorney for the plaintiffs. <PERSON> Moran </PERSON>'s ruling means the building `` will remain under <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> regulatory control. It means rent increase proposed in February were unlawful,'' <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> said. The building's owners did not return phone messages Friday and their attorney, <PERSON> Ellen </PERSON> <PERSON> Babbitt </PERSON>, refused to discuss the case. <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> called the ruling `` an influential decision in that it's the first decision of any court ... on the constitutionality of the act,'' he said `` Other courts are not bound by this judgment but we think ... it will affect their decisions'' on similar challenges to the law, he said. <PERSON> Wilen </PERSON> said one similar case is pending in federal court in <LOCATION> Raleigh </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION> `` What the law provides is that an owner who wishes to prepay -LRB- a federal mortgage -RRB- has two options. One is to prove to <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> that the prepayment and resulting rent increases would not have a harmful effect for housing opportunities for low-income people and minorities,'' <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> said. Under that option, owners `` would have to demonstrate that there's a ... surplus of low-income housing'' in their neighborhood, he said. `` If they ca n't establish that ... they can ask for additional financial incentives from <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>,'' such as an increase in subsidies, that would still keep them under federal jurisdiction, the attorney said. The owners of the <LOCATION> Buena </LOCATION> building did neither, he said.
