<SECOND>AM-Bicyclist Killed,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boy Had Past Brush With Drugs, Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 9-year-old boy who was struck by a car and killed while riding his bicycle carrying two vials of cocaine lived a tumultuous life that included a brush with death at age 4 and a drug entanglement two months ago. `` He was a nice boy, full of humor. He was really active, busy, but he really did n't do anything bad,'' said <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Butler </PERSON>, an instructor at <ORGANIZATION> Bethany </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Ministries, a church center in <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON>'s neighborhood. The last time Ms. <PERSON> Butler </PERSON> saw <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> was Nov. 29, the day he was struck by a car while pedaling his bicycle on a busy, four-lane road in suburban <LOCATION> Ross </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Township </LOCATION>. He died of head injuries Monday at <ORGANIZATION> Allegheny </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> was only 4 when his mother, <PERSON> Larita </PERSON> <PERSON> Welch </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON>, then 25, dropped him to safety from the second story of a burning tenement housing drug addicts and alcoholics in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. The Rev. <PERSON> Hurshel </PERSON> <PERSON> Langham </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, who caught <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> that day in January 1983, remembered <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> as friendly and intelligent. `` The thing that amazed me was how he was able to survive in there with all of the drunks and junkies. I was totally impressed that he could live in that environment and be so well contented,'' said <PERSON> Langham </PERSON>. Ms. <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> was convicted of arson for allegedly setting the fire, which killed four people. She was sentenced to life in prison, and <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> was sent to live with his grandparents in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>. Two months ago, police searched the home <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> lived in with his grandparents and an aunt and uncle after family members told police Sept. 2 that the aunt, 20-year-old <PERSON> Renee </PERSON> <PERSON> Welch </PERSON>, was acting as a drug courier and planned to get drugs in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, according to records in <ORGANIZATION> Allegheny </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Welch </PERSON> would not let officers search her bedroom. After police left, <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> went to his aunt's bedroom, but his uncle and grandparents stopped him as he tried to leave and found 40 bags of heroin and cocaine in his clothes. The aunt, who was charged with multiple drug offenses and corrupting a minor, is free on bond awaiting trial. Meanwhile, <LOCATION> Ross </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Township </LOCATION> police Sgt. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Zotter </PERSON> said investigators are looking for links between the vials <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> was carrying when he was struck and drug residue found in containers taken from the aunt's bedroom. Tests also showed <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> had alcohol in his blood when he was struck. Family attorney <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> said the boy was asthmatic and had been taking cough syrup that contains alcohol. The boy had been seen riding his bike erratically on the same highway in the days before he was struck, and police were responding to a similar report when the fatal accident occurred, <PERSON> Zotter </PERSON> said. The teen-age driver was charged with leaving the scene of an accident. The bike seemed to be one of the few constants in Francisco's life `` On a nice day he'd bring his bike down and park it and play out back,'' said <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, a worker at <ORGANIZATION> Bethany </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Ministries. `` He loved his bike.''
