<FIRST>u w AM-NATO-TroopsStudy     12-09 0740</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NATO-Troops Study,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Think They Could Win European War With Fewer Troops, Study
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> should be cautious about Soviet proposals for deep reductions in <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> troop levels because <LOCATION> Krelim </LOCATION> leaders believe they still could win a war with fewer soldiers than they have now, a congressional study said Friday. The report by a trio of congressional agencies was completed before the announcement of troop reductions made Wednesday by Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, in a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> speech, said the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> would reduce its military forces 10 percent worldwide. That would include the withdrawal of some Soviet troops and tanks from <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Friday's report was prepared by the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assessment </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. It was done in response to last year's <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> budget bill, which ordered a wide-ranging study of the military balance between the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and its <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact allies. The study sounded four major warnings about the onging U.S.-Soviet efforts to negotiate lower levels of troops and military power in the European theater. The cautionary notes were based on the possibility of a Soviet attack on <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>. The study said: _ `` First, because the Soviets do not believe that they must have superiority across the theater in order to achieve victory, caution must be exhibited in any agreement for force reductions.'' It noted the Soviets now enjoy at least a 2-to-1 advantage in many major measures of military might. But it noted that `` Soviet writings suggest that the Soviets could have a force advantage across the theater of as little as 1.25 to 1 _ or even parity _ and still achieve victory.'' _ `` Any overall symmetrical reduction in forces would not be to <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>'s advantage, given that lowering the density of forces, by Soviet calculations, would aid the attacker and make rapid advance and maneuvers easier.'' _ `` Unless all equipment is disabled or destroyed, the Soviets could agree to force reductions, knowing that a dramatically reduced division would be capable of regneration in a few weeks.'' _ `` Finally, <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> should not expect any significant unilateral reductions on the part of the Soviets _ either to promote good will or to pressure <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> into an equivalent response _ that would not also be in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s own military and political interests.'' The report studied Soviet military attitudes toward the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> and concluded that `` Soviet planners believe that they have a marginal advantage in the conventional balance in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> today, although they are far less optimistic about the future.'' The Soviets do n't believe they need a numerical advantage to win a military attack, the study said. `` Instead, the ability to mass at decisive places and times with sufficient forces to achieve their objectives is the key.'' While the Soviets have roughly a 2-to-1 manpower advantage now, the Soviets apparently have concluded that a 1.5-to-1 force advantage _ or even parity _ across the entire theater may be sufficient to enable their forces to achieve a 3 - or 4-to-1 force advantage on a few breakthrough sectors and 4 - to 8-to-1 advantage at the tactical point of penetration, the study The study was prepared by a variety of experts, including Comptroller General <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowsher </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>; former arms negotiator <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Dean </PERSON>; Rep. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> seapower subcommittee; <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Korb </PERSON>, former assistant secretary of defense; and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Woolsey </PERSON>, former undersecretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> The report offered no clear answer to the question of who is ahead _ <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> or the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact. It noted that `` neither side has such an overwhelming advantage that its victory would be assured.'' But it added that `` most scenarios favor the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact as the victor rather than <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> has a chance of success, but it needs to address its many shortcomings to enhance that chance.'' The study said `` despite problems in measuring the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact force balance, the experts agreed that <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>'s peacetime deterrent position is good and that its conventional capabilities have improved over the last decade, but they should be better.'' If the Soviets struck quickly, <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> likely could do a good job of defending the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>, the study said. But in a long fight, the balance might swing toward the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact because of <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> shortcomings in logistics and stockpiles of weapons and ammunition.
