<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A conservation group Friday unveiled an attempt to wrap the message of tropical forest conservation in a rap music videotape. The six-minute videotape made by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> affiliate of the World Wildlife Fund should be seen by `` 5 million to 7 million kids'' next year in 50,000 schools, said <PERSON> Grace </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lieberman </PERSON>, member of the fund staff and co-author of the teacher's manual that accompanies the tape and other materials. Interspersed with shots of exotic animals, birds, plants and reptiles in the jungles of <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, a group of youngsters about 10 years old dances through <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> streets and the <LOCATION> Botanic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Garden </LOCATION> on the Mall in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The lyrics reveal the rocky metrics, pulsing beat and sustained rhyme of typical rap numbers: `` The red-eyed frog has suction pads to cling _ `` They climb vertically, I guess that's their thing. `` Howler monkeys, now they got the style, `` Their howls can be heard over half a mile `` And that's a caiman, waiting a while `` For its prey to come, it's related to the crocodile.'' The teachers' kit was made in cooperation with the <ORGANIZATION> Smithsonian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION>, whose <ORGANIZATION> Traveling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exhibition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> is sending a tropical forest exhibit to 14 cities. The fund will give 1,000 copies of the tape and teaching materials to host institutions in those cities. Others will be asked to pay $ 20 per kit or $ 5 for the tape alone. Conservationists say 27 million acres of forest, an area bigger than <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, are lost around the world each year through logging and conversion to farmland, threatening the existence of thousands of exotic species not even studied yet by scientists, local environmental damage and exacerbation of the greenhouse effect warming of the earth. `` We surveyed teachers across the country and they told us in a world of <ORGANIZATION> MTV </ORGANIZATION> we could n't use film strips and slide shows'' and hold students attention, said Ms. <PERSON> Lieberman </PERSON>. The idea for the tape came from the rap video idea advanced by staffer <PERSON> Sally </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON>, who produced the tape. A grant of $ 75,000 from <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> supported the project.
