<HEAD>Captain in Cannibalism Case Will Be Court-Martialed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The former captain of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warship whose alleged failure to help a boatload of starving Vietnamese refugees apparently forced them to resort to cannibalism will be court-martialed, a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said Friday. Capt. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Balian </PERSON>, 48, of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, was relieved of his duties in August after Vietnamese refugees claimed the <ORGANIZATION> USS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dubuque </ORGANIZATION> did not assist them when it met up with their boat in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> on June 9. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> officials said 52 of the refugees later reached the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> but 58 died during the 37-day voyage. Survivors said two Vietnamese died of starvation but three others were slain and eaten by fellow passengers. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman Lt. Cmdr. <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Mukri </PERSON> said Friday that the commander of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> naval forces in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, Rear Adm. <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rich </PERSON>, ordered the court-martial after reviewing findings of an investigation conducted at the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Subic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> naval base and in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Dubuque </LOCATION>'s destination when it spotted the Vietnamese boat. <PERSON> Mukri </PERSON> said no date had been set for the court-martial, but it probably would be held at <LOCATION> Subic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, 50 miles west of <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>. The investigation, which corresponds to a civilian grand jury probe, was completed Oct. 28 and forwarded to <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> on Nov. 7, <PERSON> Mukri </PERSON> said. It found that the Vietnamese vessel was out of food and water and with an inoperative engine and sails when it encountered the <LOCATION> Dubuque </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Balian </PERSON> claimed the boat was seaworthy and that the crew provided food, water and navigational directions. <PERSON> Mukri </PERSON> said the investigation determined that the <LOCATION> Dubuque </LOCATION> failed to provide food, water and clothing, even though some of the refugees were naked, dehydrated, and weakened from their ordeal at sea. He said <PERSON> Balian </PERSON> faced seven charges, including failure to render assistance to a vessel in distress and failing to determine the condition of the vessel. He said <PERSON> Balian </PERSON>, who is now in <LOCATION> Sasabo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, could be dismissed from the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> and imprisoned for two years on each charge if convicted. <PERSON> Balian </PERSON> also was charged with failing to rescue a Vietnamese refugee who jumped into the water and tried to swim to the port side of the <LOCATION> Dubuque </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Mukri </PERSON> said. He said another Vietnamese tried to climb a rope ladder on the side of the <LOCATION> Dubuque </LOCATION>, but the crew shook it and he fell back into the sea. The <LOCATION> Dubuque </LOCATION> also did not report the location of the Vietnamese vessel by radio so that other ships in the area could render assistance, <PERSON> Mukri </PERSON> said. Quoting the report, <PERSON> Mukri </PERSON> said the Vietnamese vessel left <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> on May 22. By the time it encountered the <LOCATION> Dubuque </LOCATION> on June 9, there were 83 men, women and children, including one infant, still alive, the report said. Filipino fishermen later rescued the refugees. They were taken to the <LOCATION> Philippine </LOCATION> island of <LOCATION> Palawan </LOCATION>, where they were cared for by Filipino and <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> authorities. One of the refugees, 10-year-old Hung <PERSON> Quoc </PERSON> <PERSON> Tran </PERSON>, was reunited late last month with an aunt and grandmother in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dorado </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ark. </LOCATION>, about 120 miles south of <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION>.
