<TEXT>
 Soviet dissident <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> and Polish Solidarity leader <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, each making his first visit abroad since winning the Nobel Peace Prize, arrived Friday to join a human rights celebration. The two men, who were planning to meet for the first time during the weekend, were invited by President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> for ceremonies marking Saturday's 40th anniversary of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> UNESCO </ORGANIZATION> Director General <PERSON> Federico </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayor </PERSON> were scheduled to speak Saturday at the <LOCATION> Palais </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chaillot </LOCATION> overlooking the Seine that will be attended by hundreds of dignitaries, human rights activists and politicians. In <LOCATION> Oslo </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> on Friday accepted the 1988 Nobel Peace Prize check on behalf of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> peacekeeping forces. <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>, on his way back to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> following a four-week visit to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, arrived Friday morning at <LOCATION> Charles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gaulle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> and was to be joined by his wife <PERSON> Yelena </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonner </PERSON> on Friday night for the couple's first trip together outside the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, allowed to leave <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> for the first time since martial law was declared in 1981, arrived Friday night at the same airport and told reporters he was looking forward to meeting <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>. `` We both still feel, he and I, the breath of <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> at our backs,'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said, speaking Polish through an interpreter. `` After seven years, here I am at the dawn of something new,'' he said. `` The Stalin era is over. Now I am waiting for the return to pluralism and the restoration of rights.'' At a 90-minute-long news conference at the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Embassy </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> called for more steps to reduce the size of the Soviet military. The 67-year-old physicist said one way to do this would be to limit the length of service for Soviet draftees. Commenting on Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s offer Wednesday at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> to cut the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> by 500,000 and withdraw thousands of tanks and troops from <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, he said it was a major decision but only a beginning. He said reductions in manpower and weapons `` can be done and will change in a major way the international situation. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is going in this direction and this is very important. I would have liked to see bigger cuts but what was done is important.'' <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>, who helped develop the Soviet hydrogen bomb, previously was barred from traveling abroad because of his past scientific work. He was also restricted to the industrial city of <LOCATION> Gorky </LOCATION> for seven years because of his outspoken opposition to <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> intervention in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. In 1986, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> personally called him back to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. Since then, <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> has generally supported <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s perestroika, or political and economic restructuring, while speaking out against some trends, including the growing concentration of power in <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s hands. He twice sidestepped questions about the political implications of the meeting he is expected to have with <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, who is being allowed by Polish authorities to make his first trip abroad since the military crackdown on the independent union seven years ago. In an interview published Thursday in the daily <ORGANIZATION> Le </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monde </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said he believed authorities granted him the visa because <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> seeks better relations with the West `` and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> can facilitate this.'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, who won the Nobel Prize in 1983, on Thursday told the French daily Liberation that he was looking forward to meeting <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>, the 1975 prize winner. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> will confer with French trade unionists, <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, actor <PERSON> Yves </PERSON> <PERSON> Montand </PERSON>, Culture Minister <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Lang </PERSON> and Cardinal <PERSON> Jean-Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Lustiger </PERSON>, leader of the French <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> will meet <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> and Premier <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON> on Saturday. The Universal Declaration of Human Rights, adopted without dissent by the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> on Dec. 10, 1948, is the basic document under which member nations pledge to safeguard life and liberty and abolish torture and slavery. The <ORGANI