<HEAD>East Europeans Pin Hopes On Gorbachev's Pledge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By INGOMAR SCHWELZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 From Communist Party headquarters to street cafes, East Europeans are giving an enthusiastic response to Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s pledge to withdraw some Soviet troops from <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. `` It's great, for us it's a real sign of hope for peace,'' said one <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> teacher as she sat with a group of people around a table in <LOCATION> Egon-Erwin-Kisch </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cafe </LOCATION> <LOCATION> on </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>'s Unter den <PERSON> Linden </PERSON> boulevard. `` The political significance of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s words really can not be praised enough,'' said a student. Both asked that their names not be used. In a speech to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> Wednesday, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> announced a unilateral reduction of 500,000 soldiers _ 50,000 of them in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> _ including the withdrawal and disbanding of six tank divisions from <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> by 1991. Soviet allies quickly hailed the speech and said the moves were discussed with the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> in advance. <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s Communist leader <PERSON> Erich </PERSON> <PERSON> Honecker </PERSON>, who has refused to follow <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s economic and political reforms in his own country, praised the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leader's pledge. <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> `` welcomes and fully and completely supports the far-reaching new initiatives and suggestions,'' <PERSON> Honecker </PERSON> said at a state reception for <LOCATION> Yugoslav </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Raif </PERSON> <PERSON> Dizdarevic </PERSON> Wednesday. Western analysts say the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has about 380,000 troops in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, the largest force in one of its allied countries. <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s state-run television broadcast <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> speech live and official newspapers carried the full address under banner headlines. Hungarian Foreign Minister <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Varkonyi </PERSON>, who is visiting <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, was quoted by the state news agency <ORGANIZATION> MTI </ORGANIZATION> as telling a news conference there: `` I can say that together with our Chinese partners we welcomed this initiative of great significance in the greatest accord.'' Hungarian Defense Minister Gen. <PERSON> Ferenc </PERSON> <PERSON> Karpati </PERSON> was quoted as saying the Soviet withdrawal would affect about one-fourth of the Soviet troops in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, indicating about 12,000 Soviet troops would leave. The official Czechoslovak news agency <ORGANIZATION> CTK </ORGANIZATION> said Friday the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Politburo </ORGANIZATION> on Friday welcomed the Soviet initiative `` with high appreciation and full support.'' An estimated 80,000 Soviet troops in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> came to the country during the 1968 Soviet-led <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> invasion that crushed the short-lived `` Prague Spring'' of liberal reforms. Gen. <PERSON> Kamen </PERSON> <PERSON> Petrov </PERSON>, a member of the Bulgarian army general staff, described <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s announced steps as a `` program of the 21st century.'' Polish Foreign Minister <PERSON> Tadeusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Olechowski </PERSON>, in a statement issued by the official <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> news agency said: `` The announced pullbacks will contribute essentially to easing the threat of military confrontation on our continent, especially central <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Jacek </PERSON> <PERSON> Czaputowicz </PERSON>, co-founder of the unofficial group Freedom and Peace, said he hoped the move would lead to removal of all Soviet troops from <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Jacek </PERSON> <PERSON> Szymanderski </PERSON>, another co-founder of Freedom and Peace, said the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> army is `` the most important Stalinist institution in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s action was `` very important, one of the most important steps in the de-Stalinization of Soviet policy,'' he told the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> in a telephone interview.
