<FIRST>r i AM-RentBoycott     12-09 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rent Boycott,0579</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soweto City Council Drops Campaign To Crush Rent Boycott</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOWETO, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION>'s new city council will stop evicting residents of the black township who have taken part in a 3-year-old rent boycott and will not force them to pay back rent, anti-apartheid activists said Friday. The delegation of activists made the announcement after meeting with the black council for several hours. The delegation included Anglican Archbishop <PERSON> Desmond </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON>, miners union leader <PERSON> Cyril </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramaphosa </PERSON> and others who in the past have refused to negotiate with the council. The rent boycott is one of the most effective forms of protest still available to blacks under the 30-month-old state of emergency. The boycott was launched in 1985 to press a broad range of grievances against the government. Overdue rent in <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION> alone is believed to exceed $ 100 million. Authorities have used numerous tactics to try to break the boycott, including late-night eviction raids such as one in August 1986, which led to the deaths of nearly 30 blacks in a confrontation with police. Friday's meeting came two days after <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s highest court, the Appeal Court in <LOCATION> Bloemfontein </LOCATION>, ruled that previous councils of the township had no legal authority to collect rent from occupants of the thousands of homes built in the 1940s and 1950s by the city council of neighboring <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>. At the time there was no separate black administration in <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION>. The Rev. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Chikane </PERSON>, secretary-general of the South African Council of Churches and leader of the activists' delegation, said the councilors agreed that, because of the court ruling, no Sowetan was required to pay any of millions of dollars of rent withheld during the boycott. <PERSON> Chikane </PERSON> said further negotiations would take place to determine whether some residents should now be awarded ownership of their houses and what type of rent or service charges should be paid in the future. He and <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> indicated activists viewed the new council more positively than its predecessors. `` They are people who want to do good, people who honestly believe they can change the system,'' <PERSON> Chikane </PERSON> said. `` Whether they can it, subject to an apartheid <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, remains to be seen.'' `` They told us our grievances were their grievances,'' <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> said. Under <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s system of apartheid, the nation's 26-million black majority has no say in national affairs. Black local councils have been denounced by activists as subordinate extensions of the white-dominated political system. Soweto's new council took office following nationwide municipal elections Oct. 26 which were the target of an illegal but successful boycott by blacks. About 11.5 percent of the eligible voters in <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION> cast ballots. The new council, seeking to distance itself from the old ones, proceeded to rehire municipal workers fired during a strike and said it wanted to consult with community leaders to solve problems facing its 2.5 million residents. One of the consequences of the five-month municipal workers' strike was an accumulation of trash on roadsides throughout <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION> The council is launching a clean-up campaign Saturday, and drew praise from the normally critical local newspaper, The Sowetan, for a proposal to pay children to join the clean-up. The activists said in a statement Friday that negotiations with the council would continue only if it were able to guarantee that community leaders were not harassed or detained as they consulted with residents.
</TEXT>
