<SECOND>AM-Shuttle-Satellite,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Magazine Says Spy Satellite Didn't Deploy Properly on First Try</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The solar panels on the secret spy satellite launched by the shuttle <ORGANIZATION> Atlantis </ORGANIZATION> failed to swing open the first time ground controllers commanded them to, and <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> officials briefly feared the mission might fail, an industry magazine reports. But, with two astronauts standing by to take a spacewalk if necessary, a second set of radio commands freed the panels, and the satellite was successfully deployed high over the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Week </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> reported in its Dec. 12 issue. The panels are needed to absorb sunlight which powers the satellite's batteries. The magazine, citing <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> sources, said deployment of the $ 500 million <ORGANIZATION> Martin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marietta </ORGANIZATION> radar satellite took place on the shuttle's fifth orbit, or about seven hours after it was launched at 9:30 a.m. EST on Friday, Dec. 2. After the astronauts used the shuttle's robot arm to release the satellite, they kept their spaceship close enough to watch the deployment, and were able to visually confirm when it was fully open to its 150-foot span. Had it not, <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Lt. Col. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> Cmdr. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shepherd </PERSON> were prepared to take a spacewalk to repair or retrieve the satellite. The magazine said <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> Cmdr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON> first maneuvered the shuttle to a point about 3 miles from the Lacrosse, then to about 5 miles away, then further at 5-mile increments. These maneuvers were witnessed by a network of amateur astronomers linked by computers around the world and headed by <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Molczan </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, according to the magazine. It said the astronomers observed close-formation flight between the Atlantis and the Lacrosse on their sixth and seventh orbits. By Dec. 6, just before the shuttle returned to <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>, members of the group in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> observed the Lacrosse about 180 miles from <LOCATION> Atlantis </LOCATION>, the magazine said. The mission was the third entirely classified shuttle flight, and neither <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> nor the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> released any information about its purpose. However it was widely reported _ even by the official <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> _ that the Lacrosse was being deployed to observe Soviet and <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> European military operations through darkness or cloud cover. Such information would be valuable for verifying Soviet arms compliance. The satellite would also serve as a `` radar eye'' for the new B-2 stealth bomber.
