<TEXT>
 A couple who was able to move into a house through a county rent subsidy were packing to leave it Friday, three months after their garden collapsed into a sinkhole of decaying automotive batteries and they learned they were living on one of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s toxic `` superfund'' sites. `` I thought we had gone through the toughest part,'' said <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Piazza </PERSON>. `` When we got this place, I thought we were finally on the right track and we could settle.'' County officials made a `` bureaucratic mistake'' when they moved <PERSON> Piazza </PERSON> and his family into the home last March, said <PERSON> Marice </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashe </PERSON>, director of health education for <LOCATION> Contra </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. `` No one should live there,'' she said. She said tests showed that lead levels in the ground around the property, which has been on the state's toxic cleanup list since 1986, were not seriously high but were `` on the borderline of posing a health threat'' to the <PERSON> Piazza </PERSON> children. <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON>, 12, <ORGANIZATION> Crystal </ORGANIZATION>, 4, and <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, 3, have been living in temporary quarters while the move is arranged. The Piazzas spent five years living in a 25-year-old school bus and a hotel before county housing authorities helped them move into the $ 850-a-month house last March. The Piazzas paid $ 167 of the monthly total; the county subsidized the rest. <PERSON> Piazza </PERSON> said owner <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Sr. </PERSON> warned him there `` was a very slight contamination in the back behind the fence. But that's at least 50 feet away and I knew the kids would n't be playing back there.'' So they relaxed and planted a vegetable garden in the front yard. On Sept. 10, <PERSON> Piazza </PERSON> left the water on in the garden overnight. He awoke to find a hole about three feet deep and six feet wide where the garden had been, and a sinkhole filled with old automotive battery parts. It's now about 15 feet wide, <PERSON> Piazza </PERSON> said. `` I was so shocked it took a few minutes for me just to get my thoughts together,'' he said. `` It caused a lot of scared confusion in our minds because we did n't know what it had done to us or our kids.'' `` Here we had been growing vegetables on top of all those things and eating the crops for more than two months,'' <PERSON> Piazza </PERSON> said. Cost of the cleanup is estimated at $ 1 million. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> voters approved a state superfund program in November 1984 to raise funds to clean up toxic waste sites, modeled after the federal superfund program. The <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> site was reported to county health authorities in 1985, and was put on the state cleanupt list the following year, though not at the top. The county advised the state health department that the cleanup could be put off a few years because an elderly couple aware of the possible contamination problem was living there. Lead is particularly dangerous for children. State health spokeswoman <PERSON> Jill </PERSON> <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON> said then-owner R.D. <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> agreed to notify the county if property use changed. But deputy district attorney <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Sepulveda </PERSON> said <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> failed to notify the county when he sold the property. <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> said the county knew he had planned to sell the land. According to <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON>, <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> is legally and financially liable for the cleanup, which could cost up to $ 1 million.
