<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A lawyer for eight <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> sanctuary workers told a federal appeals court Friday the defendants believed the Central American aliens they aided were refugees with a right to live in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Attorney <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Tigar </PERSON> told a three-judge panel of the 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> that a trial judge in <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>, improperly barred the sanctuary workers from presenting evidence of their beliefs concerning the refugees from strife-torn nations. A government attorney, urging the court to uphold the convictions of all eight defendants, said it was clear the workers never believed they were acting legally and knew that smuggling aliens was against the law. There was no immediate ruling on the appeal. At a news conference following the court session, one of those convicted, <PERSON> Peggy </PERSON> <PERSON> Hutchison </PERSON>, vowed that the sanctuary movement would go on regardless of the outcome of the case. `` We have a duty to respond to the violated in our midst,'' she said. The eight, including five clergymen, were convicted on various charges of conspiracy, transporting and harboring and aiding illegal entry of aliens in a highly publicized 1986 trial. All received probation. Several other defendants were acquitted, pleaded guilty to misdemeanors or won dismissal of charges. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Reno </PERSON>, who prosecuted the case in <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION>, said their conspiracy was clearly illegal. `` In this case, these defendants were methodically smuggling these aliens into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` Everything they were doing was surreptitious and clandestine.'' He said the def