<HEAD>Two-Thirds Of Inmates On Work Release At Non-Traditional Prison Are
Murderers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JESSUP, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two-thirds of the inmates granted work-release status at the controversial Patuxent Institution are murderers and nearly 60 percent are serving life terms, according to prison statistics. The Patuxent Institution, which emphasizes rehabilitation through psychotherapy, came under criticism last week when convicted rapist <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stavarakas </PERSON> fled while on work-release and allegedly raped a woman in <LOCATION> Hyattsville </LOCATION>. He was arrested Sunday. Earlier, it was revealed that triple killer <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Daly </PERSON> <PERSON> Angell </PERSON> was granted several unsupervised furloughs. Citing the criticism and <PERSON> Stavarakas </PERSON>' escape, the Patuxent board of review voted Dec. 1 to suspend all furloughs and work release programs indefinitely. Lifers turn up more often in Patuxent's work-release and leave programs than do inmates from the prison's general population, according to the figures released Thursday by the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Correctional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>. While those serving life sentences represent about one in five Patuxent inmates, they make up 59 percent of those on work-release and 28 percent of those on leave, the figures showed. The figures also showed that inmates serving life terms at Patuxent serve only half as much time as do lifers at other <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> prisons before they are granted parole. The 16 Patuxent lifers paroled from July 1, 1977, to June 30, 1988, served an average of 8.4 years before release. Life inmates at other <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> prisons are confined 17 years on average before parole, saidDr. <PERSON> Norma </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gluckstern </PERSON>, Patuxent's director. Patuxent is unusual because of the wide authority given to prison officials to grant leaves to inmates, although a 1982 law requires approval by the governor before an inmate serving for life is paroled. Several state lawmakers have suggested that further restrictions be placed on the prison's governing board. Inmates are sent to Patuxent because correction officials consider them more likely to be rehabilitated through its program of psychological and psychiatric counseling.
