<HEAD>Soviet Scientists Competing For Use of Controversial Radar,
Official Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet scientists are competing with each other to develop a research project for the scientific use of a controversial military radar, the president of the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> said Friday. <PERSON> Guriy </PERSON> <PERSON> Marchuk </PERSON>, who leads the Soviet academy, said that at least four scientific uses for the large radar station at <LOCATION> Krasnoyarsk </LOCATION> have been proposed to the academy, but no final decision has been made. The radar, located in a remote sector of central <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION>, was turned over to the Soviet academy by Soviet president <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> after the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration claimed that it was a violation of the anti-ballistic missile treaty between the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The radar is neither on the edge of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> nor is it pointed outward, as is required by the ABM treaty. It is believed by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> experts that the radar was built for the detection and tracking of ballistic missiles. <PERSON> Marchuk </PERSON>, who lectured Friday at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION>, was asked what the Soviet academy planned to do with the radar. `` We do n't know,'' <PERSON> Marchuk </PERSON> replied through an interpreter. `` We have declared a competition or contest'' to find the best use for the radar station. `` We have at least four projects suggesting what we should do with it,'' he added. He said the proposals include both space and atmospheric research. <PERSON> Marchuk </PERSON>, speaking to an audience of American researchers, said that scientists everywhere may participate in the competition. `` I invite all of those with ideas to come up with proposals and send them to us,'' he said. In his lecture, <PERSON> Marchuk </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> now is applying democratic principles in selecting the scientific leadership of the nation. He said there are about 520 academic institutions in the <ORGANIZATION> USSR </ORGANIZATION> and that they all recently selected new leaders on a `` competitive basis.'' `` More than half of the academic institutions now are headed by young people,'' said <PERSON> Marchuk </PERSON>. `` This is possible only in the atmosphere of democracy.'' The academy president said he regarded this as a good development for Soviet science because `` the best ideas come into the minds of people under the age of 30. After 30 they just develop their ideas.'' <PERSON> Marchuk </PERSON> gave the lecture on the opening day of a conference marking the 30th year of cooperatation and exchange between the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and the <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> of the <ORGANIZATION> USSR </ORGANIZATION>.
