<HEAD>Rocard's Government Survives First Censure Vote</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Socialist Premier <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON>'s minority government survived its first <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> censure vote early Saturday when <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> members refused to back the conservative opposition. Only 258 legislators, all members of rightist or center-right parties, voted for the censure motion. Under the French Constitution, the government is forced to resign on a censure motion only if an absolute majority _ 286 out of 571 _ votes for it, not just a majority of those voting. Only votes in favor are recorded. There are no abstentions or votes against. Six seats are vacant in the 577-member chamber of deputies, the lower house. <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON> has been widely criticized for his handling of a series of strikes by public employees, including one that has disrupted subway, bus and suburban train service for the past two weeks. But he was in no danger of losing the censure vote. `` <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> is at an impasse,'' <PERSON> Philippe </PERSON> <PERSON> Seguin </PERSON>, speaking for the conservative Rally for the Republic party, said in the censure debate. `` A country needs to be led, to know where it's going, how it's getting there and why it's going there.'' <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> it was a `` motion of spite'' presented because the right was `` embitterred by its defeat'' in this year's presidential and legislative elections. He called the motion `` an operation of political diversion, with its result known in advance and with no effect on the political or social climate.'' The debate began Friday night and lasted past midnight. The current chamber of deputies is made up of 273 Socialists, 130 members of the Rally for the Republic, 89 from the center-right <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> French </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION>, 41 in the Union of the Center, 24 Communists and 14 independents. President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> named <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON> premier last May after winning re-election to a new seven-year term. In June's legislative elections, the Socialists fell short of winning a majority in the chamber, but did well enough to prevent the right from taking control.
