<HEAD>Americans Organize Relief Efforts For Armenia</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 18 grafs to UPDATE with dog team plans; relief
activities launched in Rhode Island, Illinois, Washington, Boston,
California, elsewhere; picks up 8th graf: `In Oregon ...; ADDS 2
grafs with Ohio fund drive.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Americans are responding to the earthquake in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> with offers of medical supplies, doctors, money, specially trained dogs and prayers. As Soviet officials reported 80,000 people died in the disaster Wednesday in northwestern <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> collected money, antibiotics and supplies and groups throughout the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> began efforts to help the survivors. <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>'s Gov. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> DiPrete </PERSON> offered to send his state's <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> to <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> if President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> approves `` It's just a willingness to help in whatever way possible,'' <PERSON> DiPrete </PERSON> said. The <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> chapter of the Armenian <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Benevolent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, began accepting relief donations, including two or more ambulances for the disaster area, said the group's treasurer, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Klujian </PERSON>. The ambulance contributor, who lives in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, `` sent the money to the manufacturer in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and is having them sent directly to the earthquake area,'' <PERSON> Klujian </PERSON> said. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, an Armenian Diocese Earthquake Fund was set up at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mary </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armenian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>. During a memorial service, its pastor, the Rev. <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kalayjian </PERSON>, described the devastation as `` the disaster that fell on us like a bomb.'' Boston-based <ORGANIZATION> Oxfam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> donated $ 20,000 for temporary shelter and medical supplies, its first relief effort in an industrialized nation and in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, officials said. Members of the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Disaster Dog Search and <ORGANIZATION> Rescue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Team </ORGANIZATION> headed to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and planned to go to <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> to aid in search efforts, officials said Friday. Team members from <ORGANIZATION> Northeast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Search </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rescue </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Dogs </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, were summoned from their homes across the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> and gathered at <LOCATION> JFK </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on Friday. Eight dogs, their handlers, equipment and a two-week supply of dog food were to be flown to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> aboard a jet flight arranged by the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Judi </PERSON> <PERSON> Kroeger </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for <LOCATION> Allentown </LOCATION>, Pa.-based <ORGANIZATION> Alpo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petfoods </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which sponsors the units. Specific flight times had not been set, but the jet was to fly first to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Dulles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> and leave for the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION>