<HEAD>Dinner With Miss Ruby and Friends</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY MacVEAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A holiday dinner as sassy and sumptuous as the one Miss Ruby serves up is a feast indeed. The table is set Tuesday on PBS for `` Miss <PERSON> Ruby </PERSON>'s Southern Holiday Dinner,'' and even <ORGANIZATION> Yankees </ORGANIZATION> will feel right at home with <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> restaurateur <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> <PERSON> Bronz </PERSON>, aka `` Miss Ruby,'' and her guests: humorist <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Blount </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, entertainer <PERSON> Pearl </PERSON> <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON>, <PERSON> Annie </PERSON> <PERSON> Potts </PERSON> of `` Designing Women,'' and food writer <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Claiborne </PERSON>. Together they cook, eat and talk about some of the hallmarks of a Southern Christmas feast _ <ORGANIZATION> Smithfield </ORGANIZATION> ham, which `` looks funny, tastes real good,'' says <PERSON> Bronz </PERSON>; red-eye gravy; red snapper stuffed with crab; turkey and cornbread stuffing; scalloped oysters and derby pie. It's a delightful hour, for cooks and for eaters. <PERSON> Bronz </PERSON>, whose restaurant features a changing menu of regional American foods, was `` raised in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> by a <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> grandmother'' and so qualifies as a Southern cook. But she acknowledges at the start that some will disagree with her version of the dishes: `` Every Southerner believes his South is the only true one.'' Her guests come from <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> -LRB- <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON> -RRB-, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> -LRB- <PERSON> Blount </PERSON> -RRB-, <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> -LRB- <PERSON> Potts </PERSON> -RRB-, and <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> -LRB- <PERSON> Claiborne </PERSON> -RRB-, and have a range of experience in the kitchen. <PERSON> Blount </PERSON>, for instance, mostly puts things in and takes things out of the oven, tastes the food, and comments on it: `` This is the prettiest ham. I've seen little children that were n't as pretty.'' Over cocktails, <PERSON> Potts </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bronz </PERSON> laugh about fruitcakes and <ORGANIZATION> Yankees </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> Claiborne </PERSON> and <PERSON> Blount </PERSON> discuss childhood Christmases, including <PERSON> Claiborne </PERSON>'s memories of breakfasts of quail and ham with red-eye gravy and grits. When <PERSON> Claiborne </PERSON> makes his cornbread stuffing, he notes that it's `` not essential to cook these innards until they're quite well-done'' because they'll cook in the turkey But <PERSON> Blount </PERSON> wanders into the kitchen, takes a handful of stuffing and bites into a raw giblet, which <PERSON> Claiborne </PERSON> calls `` chicken gizzard sashimi.'' At one point, <PERSON> Bronz </PERSON> coerces <PERSON> Blount </PERSON> and <PERSON> Potts </PERSON> to pick crab for the snapper stuffing. As they work on a big pile of blue crabs, they giggle and reminisce, and <PERSON> Blount </PERSON>, who steals a few bites and gets caught with crabmeat on the end of his nose, lets on that he's borrowed <PERSON> Claiborne </PERSON>'s apron `` When I used to try to cook things, people used to say, ` You could n't wear <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Claiborne </PERSON>'s apron.' But I showed them,''' he says. When <PERSON> Bronz </PERSON> was working with producer <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Kanter </PERSON> and director <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolkowitz </PERSON> to plan `` Miss <PERSON> Ruby </PERSON>'s Southern Holiday Dinner,'' it was decided to try to fit the celebrity guests in with the cooking, said <PERSON> Bronz </PERSON>. That's authentic, <PERSON> Bronz </PERSON> said in a telephone interview, explaining that her grandmother's generation would make long trips across the prairie `` for house parties that would last six weeks over the holidays. And I think that was in my mind in some way... I had a real vision of these people being in my kitchen.'' The result is comfortable and welcoming, what <PERSON> Kanter </PERSON> calls a `` comedy-cooking-talk'' show. <PERSON> Bronz </PERSON> said she worried a little that the food would be overwhelmed by all the commotion, but when serious work is under way in the kitchen, the directions are clear and concise and easy to follow. Viewers also can send for recipes. `` I really think good food is riveting. I do n't think people will wander from that,'' <PERSON> Bronz </PERSON> said. `` And we really set it up so that when we were n't making food, we were talking about it. Southerners just love to talk about food, and if they're not talking about food, they're talking about family. And sometimes they're talking about food and family.'' There are dishes for cooks of all abilities. <PERSON> Potts </PERSON> makes her derby pie in less than 5 minutes, and many people will sympathize when she zaps the butter too long in a microwave oven and declares, `` It's spitting at me.'' <PERSON> Potts </PERSON> even admits she does n't make her own crust for her pie of pecans, chocolate chips, eggs and sugar. After filming, the food was donated to a shelter for homeless people. The show is intended as the first of a series on American regional cooking, including future similar holiday specials. <PERSON> Bronz </PERSON> said she is on a `` mission'' to promote American food, announcing at the start: `` It's Miss <PERSON> Ruby </PERSON>'s job to see that great American food goes public.'' Wish her well, for then we all can see more of Miss Ruby.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Elsewhere in television: CHANGING DESKS IN <LOCATION> WASHINGTON </LOCATION> _ <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> has made <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> assignment changes in the wake of the decision by <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> correspondent <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> to go to <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Cochran </PERSON>, formerly at the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, succeeds <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> at the White House; also covering the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> will be <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Miklaszewski </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sandy </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilmour </PERSON>, who returns from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> next month; <PERSON> Andrea </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, who was at the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, becomes chief congressional correspondent; political correspondent <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Bode </PERSON> is also on the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> beat. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dancy </PERSON> takes over at State. <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> will be backup there and also cover the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration's war on drugs. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Pettit </PERSON> gets a newly created beat, `` poverty and the American underclass.''
