<HEAD>Glasnost Has Not Entered House Where Trotsky Was Killed</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The grandson of <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Trotsky </PERSON> sat in the room where one of <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s assassins killed the old revolutionary with an ax and pondered how far the new, more enlightened <PERSON> Kremlin </PERSON> would go toward making amends. `` If glasnost wants to have authenticity ... it must recognize the proper place of <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Trotsky </PERSON>'' in history, <PERSON> Esteban </PERSON> <PERSON> Volkow </PERSON> <PERSON> Bronstein </PERSON> said, using the word denoting the more open Soviet policies of <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. The latest sign of change came Dec. 6, when <PERSON> Volkow </PERSON> received permission to visit his half-sister <PERSON> Alexandra </PERSON>, who is dying of cancer in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. He has not been to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> or seen his sister in 57 years, and learned only last month that she was alive. `` It's all part of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policy,'' <PERSON> Volkow </PERSON> said, and <PERSON> Trotsky </PERSON> has been emerging slowly from `` the dark cave'' of Soviet history since glasnost began. `` For 50 or 60 years the <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> public has been conditioned to think of him as almost the devil,'' his grandson said. `` You ca n't change black to white in one day. <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Trotsky </PERSON>, born <PERSON> Lev </PERSON> <PERSON> Davidovich </PERSON> <PERSON> Bronstein </PERSON> in 1879, was among the most popular leaders of the 1917 Bolshevik revolution _ commander of the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, commissar for war and foreign affairs, the right hand of <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON>. After losing a power struggle with <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>, he became a `` non-person.'' <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> exiled him in 1929 and <PERSON> Trotsky </PERSON>'s name was stricken from Soviet history. Photographs and film were doctored to erase his image. Real and imagined followers were hunted down, and imprisoned or killed. <PERSON> Trotsky </PERSON>'s road ended on a summer afternoon in at his desk in the modest house in <LOCATION> Coyoacan </LOCATION>, in those days was a quiet village. <LOCATION> Coyoacan </LOCATION> is enveloped by the smog of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> now, but in the house itself little has change since the assassin entered it Aug. 20, 1940, with a mountaineer's ice ax. It has no plaques, polished display cases or uniformed guards, but there is a caretaker to greet visitors. He answers the bell, shows them through the rooms and hands them the guest book to sign. `` There was a terrible solitude, an emptiness here in the house,'' <PERSON> Volkow </PERSON> said, remembering the years after the assassination. He was born in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to <PERSON> Trotsky </PERSON>'s daughter <PERSON> Zina </PERSON> and now is 62, a semi-retired chemical engineer. <PERSON> Trotsky </PERSON>'s house always has attracted a few Soviet visitors, he said, but more have come in the past year or so. `` They are opening windows in <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Volkow </PERSON> said. `` They are turning on the light. There is a freshness.'' Glasnost has not altered <PERSON> Trotsky </PERSON>'s official status but his name sometimes is mentioned publicly and the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> rehabilitated a son, <PERSON> Volkow </PERSON>'s step-uncle <PERSON> Sergei </PERSON> <PERSON> Sedov </PERSON>, who died in a Stalin purge. In September, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> newspaper Pravda called <PERSON> Trotsky </PERSON> an `` enemy of Stalin'' rather than an enemy of `` socialism'' and the revolution. `` I believe that his heroic struggle, almost alone, against one of the most terrible, the bloodiest tyrannies in history is the stage of his life that is going to have the most historical importance,'' <PERSON> Volkow </PERSON> said. A quiet river that ran behind <PERSON> Trotsky </PERSON>'s house two generations ago has become a stream of vehicles belching fumes on a freeway, but in the shadowed rooms, behind thick walls, time seems congealed. `` It's curious. He did n't live here long ... but he impregnated the house with his presence,'' the grandsom said. Beside the reading lamp, the dictaphone waits next to books in French, German, Russian, Spanish and English on <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>, capitalism, Italian fascism, colonialism, British trade unionism. The bloodstains on <PERSON> Trotsky </PERSON>'s chair have faded but bullet holes from an earlier assassination attempt still pock the bedroom walls. He had the windows shuttered with steel and the gateway bricked up after the attack May 24, 1940, by Mexican Stalinists with machine guns. Three months later, a Stalinist agent who had insinuated himself into the <PERSON> Trotsky </PERSON> circle attacked with the ice ax. When <PERSON> Volkow </PERSON>, then 14, entered the room his grandfather lay on the floor, bleeding, his wife at his side. The assassin spent 20 years in prison but his identity never was confirmed. He was thought to be a Spaniard, <PERSON> Ramon </PERSON> <PERSON> del </PERSON> <PERSON> Rio </PERSON> <PERSON> Mercader </PERSON>, but also was known as <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Mornard </PERSON> and <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Volkow </PERSON> said <PERSON> Trotsky </PERSON> treated each day after the May attack as a bonus: `` Every morning after he got up, he would say ` Another day of life, <PERSON> Natalia </PERSON>. Another day of life.''' <PERSON> Natalia </PERSON> <PERSON> Sedov </PERSON>, <PERSON> Trotsky </PERSON>'s second wife, lived in the house for more than 20 years after the assassination. She died in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> in 1962. In the garden, a simple gray stone monument carved with a hammer and sickle encloses the ashes of <PERSON> Trotsky </PERSON> and <PERSON> Natalia </PERSON>. A red flag flutters overhead.
</TEXT>
