<NOTE>$Adv11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Dec. 11, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Fast-Food Joints Don't Want to Be Homeless Shelters</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Death on the Sidewalk, b0783-b0784 of Dec. 8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT DVORCHAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Burger King near <LOCATION> Penn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Station </LOCATION> lets homeless customers have it their way, up to a point. The welcome ends if owners think the restaurant is becoming a stopgap shelter for smelly transients. `` Sometimes it's difficult to put people out because you know they have no place to go,'' said night manager <PERSON> Cecil </PERSON> <PERSON> Murray </PERSON>. `` But you ca n't have vagrants. It scares the normal customers. `` Some come in for five or 10 minutes just to get warm and wo n't buy anything Some end up sitting there with the same thing for an hour. I ask them to leave. I ca n't have my boss see the whole place full of vagrants,'' he said. A week ago, a homeless alcoholic man was dragged from a fast food eatery in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> and deposited on the sidewalk after passing out over his meal. He lay there five hours before anyone noticed he was dead. Homeless advocates decried the incident as a too-common example of society's callousness. The <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> episode highlights the predicament of fast-food restaurants, which have become beacons for the homeless. They do n't want to banish people to the streets, but neither do they want their family atmosphere disrupted by shabby creatures, sometimes lugging all their worldly possessions in shopping bags and carts Some places deal with the problem by posting time limits. The Burger King on Eighth Avenue allows no customer to linger longer than 20 minutes. `` It's fast food. We need the seating space,'' said manager <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Barnes </PERSON>. `` But if someone passed out inside, I would call an ambulance. You just ca n't carry them out to the street, especially if they had made a purchase.'' Other places make case-by-case decisions. `` If they smell and bother other customers, we tell them to leave,'' said <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Choe </PERSON>, who runs a McDonald's on Canal Street in lower <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>. `` We do n't set a limit on how much money or how much time they spend, as long as nobody is offended,'' said <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON>, manager of a McDonald's near Grand Central Station. `` If someone in a suit and tie is being a real pain, we would escort them out.'' Advocates say thousands of homeless seek refuge in subway cars, train stations, bus depots or burger joints. `` There are parts of the country I've been in where the local <ORGANIZATION> Dunkin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Donuts </ORGANIZATION> is an emergency shelter by default,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON>, founder of the city's Coalition for the Homeless. `` As night follows day, a human being afflicted by a cold wind is going to look for refuge,'' <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON> said. `` But nobody with a reasonable option is going to sleep in a McDonald's. If there were reasonable alternatives, this problem would disappear.'' An estimated 30,000 to 45,000 people stay in abandoned buildings or public places nightly in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, not counting the ones sleeping in shelters, <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON> said. An October survey by the <ORGANIZATION> Transit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> found 1,404 homeless living in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> subways. Nationwide, no accurate census exists, but an estimated 3 million people are without homes, according to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Homeless </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> D.C </ORGANIZATION>. It agrees that restaurants make lousy sleeping quarters. `` These places are not designed to function as housing,'' said <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Foscarinis </PERSON>, spokeswoman for the coalition. `` But there is no place else to go.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Dec. 11</NOTE>
