<HEAD>Irish Potato Farmers Fight for a Future</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>'s potato farmers, who have a most colorful past, now are fighting for a future. Harried by falling demand and rising imports, the spud raisers are modernizing in order to compete.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WILKINSTOWN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It was a dismal day, wet and cold and gray _ the things most hateful about December. A few potatoes were rotting and their smell was vile, but <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheridan </PERSON> did n't seem to mind. Tramping across a muck-filled yard in his rubber boots, the 42-year-old potato farmer showed a visitor around with typical Irish generosity of time and spirit. Highlights of the tour of J and <ORGANIZATION> C </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sheridan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, one of <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>'s biggest potato farms, included a new bagging machine and storehouses full of those humblest of tubers, whose irregular shapes and skins of homespun brown inspire instant affection `` We are putting our potatoes in much more attractive packaging,'' said <PERSON> Sheridan </PERSON>, who is spending about 630,000 Irish pounds -LRB- nearly $ 1 million -RRB- to modernize the farm. `` The emphasis all the time, every single day, is better quality. I am ensuring that my market will be there.'' Welcome to the brave new world of the Irish potato industry, launching the praties of legend into the 21st century. <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>'s potato farmers, who have a most colorful past, are fighting for a future dimmed by imports and a drop in demand. In the 19th century, potatoes were the staple food of <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> and blight caused a cruel famine. Lately, the Irish have strayed to such exotic foods as pasta and farmers are trying to woo them back by, among other things, developing better-looking potatoes. What is a good-looking potato? `` What's a good-looking man?'' responded <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Burke </PERSON>, general manager of <ORGANIZATION> Irish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Potato </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marketing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Dublin </LOCATION>, about 30 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Wilkinstown </LOCATION>. `` Very subjective,'' he concluded. The ideal spud is said to be large, well-rounded and shallow-eyed. Presentation matters, too. Farmers are packaging their products better, offering consumers cleaner potatoes in smaller quantities and more uniform sizes. They are investing in better machinery and storage facilities, breeding higher-yield varieties that are more resistant to disease and will deliver larger crops per acre. They now export, to counter imports from other Common Market countries, and support development of a potato processing industry. Experts say the effort is paying off. <PERSON> Gerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Doherty </PERSON> of the government's <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> said a long decline in output is stabilizing. The total was 400,000 tons last year and is expected to be about 370,000 for 1988, he said. Imports are expected to be 30,000 tons this year and exports 13,400. A ton of potatoes brings about 90 pounds -LRB- $ 140 -RRB-. `` I'd say we're more competitive,'' <PERSON> Doherty </PERSON> said. Potatoes have been grown in <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> for more than 350 years and are woven into its culture and history. They have inspired poems and songs. They conjure many images, warm as Irish stew or wrenching as famine and emigration. `` So great has been its influence that the potato and the Irishman are often considered as somewhat synonymous,'' potato expert <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> McGivern </PERSON> wrote. Spaniards brought potatoes to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> in the 16th century. English explorer Sir <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Raleigh </PERSON> usually gets the credit for introducing them to the Emerald Isle. <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> was the first European country to grow potatoes on a large scale. By the early 1840s they were the main food for one-third of its 8 million people. Planting reached a peak of 2.5 million acres in 1845 but blight destroyed the crop and caused the Great Famine of 1845-1849, a catastrophe that killed an estimated 1 million people and caused another million to leave. Emigration continues and the birth rate is declining, so <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>'s population now is but 3.4 million and potato acreage is a mere 75,000. Commercial growers, once tens of thousands, number only 6,000. <PERSON> Burke </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Dublin </LOCATION> potato dealer, said <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>'s entry into the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> in 1973 `` has created competition, and a lot of people were not ready to cope.'' `` People are now eating things which are considered alien to the Irish character, such as pasta and rice,'' he said. Use of potatoes for industrial alcohol and animal feed has declined. With more women working and incomes growing, fewer potatoes are peeled and cooked at home. Per capita consumption fell to 244 pounds in 1984 from 260 pounds in 1980, but still is nearly double that of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Sheridan </PERSON> surveyed the farm where he first planted 12 acres of potatoes in 1967 and today grows 250 acres of <PERSON> Kerr </PERSON>'s <PERSON> Pink </PERSON>, the Irish favorite. `` We are managing to meeting the challenge,'' he said. `` We believe we'll be in business another 20 years.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Dec. 18</NOTE>
