<HEAD>Reporter's Notebook: Gorby Bites the Big Apple</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HUGH A. MULLIGAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 On his suddenly shortened visit, Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> achieved every out-of-towner's dream of making it big in the Big Apple. He saw his name in lights on <LOCATION> Broadway </LOCATION>. As his 45-car motorcade moved through Times Square at the height of rush hour, one of those huge news headline display signs flashed `` Welcome, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>.'' The chairman of the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet got the friendly message. At the corner of 5lst and Broadway, the tank-like Zil limousine came to a halt, a smiling <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> stepped out and began pressing the flesh as the crowd chanted `` <LOCATION> Gorby </LOCATION>! <LOCATION> Gorby </LOCATION>!'' His startled security detail, led by bomb squad vans and a legion of motorcycles, executed an illegal U-turn that further confounded cross-town traffic already immobilized by `` Gorby-lock.'' Here are other scenes from a reporter's notebook on the brief visit of the statesman-tourist from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>: _ Something like 180,000 commuters heeded Mayor <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>'s warning against coming to town during <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s visit. The number of vehicles entering <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> by bridge and tunnel dropped 20 percent, bringing about a new Christmas miracle on 34th Street in the vicinity of <ORGANIZATION> Macy </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> department store, where a police inspector observed that traffic was `` no more chaotic than normal.'' The motorcade's l6-minute dash from the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> to South Ferry was the envy of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> taxi drivers and should qualify as a modern record in daylight hours. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s traffic commissars were serious. They even posted parking meters with signs in Russian: `` Do n't Even Think of Parking.'' _ When the curtains were drawn, the squat, highly polished, somewhat antiquated Soviet black limousines flown in with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> looked as if they had strayed off course from a Mafia funeral along Mulberry Street. Cabbies, however, had high praise for the Russians behind the wheel. `` Being wheel man in a motorcade is real tsuriss,'' said taxi driver <PERSON> Moishe </PERSON> <PERSON> Abramson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ridge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>, using the Yiddish word for tension and trouble. `` <LOCATION> Gorby </LOCATION>'s visit buried the old joke we had around the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> about a <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> motorcade being a 10-car pile-up with flags.'' _ On the `` Tonight Show'' <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> had a topical gag about <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s promised half-million cut in Soviet troop strength: `` Soon the Russians will be down to just one obsolete tank, driven by <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>.'' _ Coast Guard Capt. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Garwin </PERSON> estimated he had made `` 6,400 crossings'' on the five-minute Governors Island ferry run before being grabbed by news anchors <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Brokaw </PERSON> and <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON> for prime-time interviews. And with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> aboard, this was the first time police frog men in their wet suits had inspected the hull of the ferry <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Coursen </PERSON> minutes before lines were cast off. _ Two <ORGANIZATION> Transit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> cops amused the crowd outside the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> by harmonizing on `` <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> and <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>,'' to the tune of `` Some Enchanted Evening,'' while waiting for the motorcade to roll by the cathedral of capitalism. _ <PERSON> Raisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, the style-conscious Soviet first lady who calls designer <PERSON> Givenchy </PERSON> by his first name of <PERSON> Hubert </PERSON>, helped bury the cartoon caricature of frumpy <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> women in galoshes and babushkas. In a visit to <PERSON> Estee </PERSON> <PERSON> Lauder </PERSON>'s Fifth Avenue beauty salon, she was sprayed with a fragrance called `` White Linen'' by the cosmetic queen herself, who plans to open a branch soon on <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s Gorky Street. <PERSON> Raisa </PERSON> also made a brief stop outside <ORGANIZATION> Bloomigdale </ORGANIZATION>'s, the upscale market version of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s Gum department store, but did n't have time to flash her American Express card According to rumors spread by refuseniks, she never leaves her dacha without it. Some Christmas shoppers like <PERSON> Faye </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernardi </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Ozone </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, thought they detected the `` look of longing in her eyes that we women get when afflicted with that shop-until-you drop syndrome.'' Or maybe it was the look a Muscovite gets when peering into the windows of a <LOCATION> Beryozka </LOCATION> shop, where luxury goods can be bought only with foreign currency. _ Nearly 60 students protesting on behalf of Soviet Jews were arrested on the final night of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s visit, but the number of demonstrators fell far below what police had anticipated. Among a variety of ethnic and political dissenters was a small group of animals lovers fuming against <PERSON> Raisa </PERSON>'s broadtail Persian taupe topcoat and Russian lynx fur hat with signs proclaiming `` minx stinx.'' _ The visit, of course, was a media carnival. One of the more ingenious sideshows featured a Canadian actor, a <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> look-alike, who conned super capitalist <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> into a hoax interview after the real Soviet leader had turned down an invitation to visit his $ 19 million apartment in Trump Tower. _ A yogurt emporium in the alley behind the stock exchange dressed up its luncheon menu with a message in the Cyrillic alphabet. Translated it read: `` Have a nice glasnost.'' _ With <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> gazing meaningfully at the Statue of Liberty from <ORGANIZATION> Liberty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Point </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Governors </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> had its most memorable historical happening since <PERSON> Wouter </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Twiller </PERSON>, the second Dutch governor of the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, purchased the 173-acre tract from local Indians for two axe heads and a fistful of nails and named it <LOCATION> Nutten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>. On a sparkling day, the tiny island with its sudden promise of long sought world peace almost seemed the inspiration for the closing paragraphs of <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzgerald </PERSON>'s `` The Great Gatsby'': `` The old island that flowered once for Dutch sailor's eyes _ a fresh, green breast of the New World. Its vanished trees had once pandered in whispers to the last and greatest of all human dreams. For a transitory enchanted moment man must have held his breath in the presence of this continent, compelled into an aesthetic contemplation he neither understood nor desired, face to face for the last time in history with something commensurate to his capacity for wonder.'' Around the Big Apple, the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gorby </LOCATION> made a substantive contribution to man's capacity for wonder.
