<HEAD>`The Russians Are Coming' Is History: They've Been Here for Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s peacemaking <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> visit and the opening of a glitzy Soviet trade show underscored the importance the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leader attaches to developing business and commercial ties in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>. But perhaps unknown to many Westerners, the Communist superpower has long been dabbling in overseas ventures that range from currency speculation in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to fish canning in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. While <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> may reduce the Soviet military, as he pledged in a speech at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, experts on the Soviet bloc said they believe his broader reforms likely will make the Soviets much more aggressive in foreign investing, exporting and competing for customers in an increasingly global economy. `` They're beginning to talk about more direct investment abroad, focused on firms that might help them market their own products,'' said <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Hewitt </PERSON>, a Soviet economics expert at the <ORGANIZATION> Brookings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> research organization. `` I would n't be at all surprised if they come in and buy out some small European or <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> firms in the next few years.'' The Soviets have not acquired any significant Western companies yet, but the number of foreign firms owned wholly or partly by the Soviets has risen sharply from about a dozen in the early 1960s to more than 120 now, said <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON>, a Soviet expert at <ORGANIZATION> Carleton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Ottawa </LOCATION>. <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON>, who has compiled a list of Soviet bloc-owned companies in the West for the past 10 years, said many of these ventures reflect a growing sophistication about investing abroad. `` There are different ways in which they do it,'' he said. `` They have assets, portfolios and direct investments. They're in a wide range of business areas: banks, insurance, engineering, shipping and commercial companies.'' The Soviet investment presence abroad remains minuscule by Western standards, however, considering that just one <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> or Japanese conglomerate might have 120 foreign subsidiaries. Still, the Soviets appear to be catching on. `` As they participate in the world economy, they've found this is the way everybody else plays the game,'' <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON> said. In <LOCATION> Scandinavia </LOCATION>, for example, the Soviets have established a chain of government-owned service stations to sell one of their biggest exports, petroleum. On this side of the world, the Soviets have stakes in two North American fishing and fish-processing concerns, <ORGANIZATION> Cansov </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Nova </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Scotia </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. International in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> As one of the largest producers of agricultural machinery and equipment, the Soviets have long been in the business of selling tractors. In 1972, they formed <ORGANIZATION> Belarus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equipment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, a Toronto-based marketer of Soviet farm vehicles. A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> branch was formed five years later, with offices in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION>. `` I would say this sort of trend will continue, and under <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> it will be more dynamic,'' said <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON>. `` I do n't think ` The Russians Are Coming' thing really fits. They've been around for awhile.'' The Soviets also are veteran participants in the world's speculative foreign-exchange markets, trading largely through two government-owned banks, <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Norodny </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Eurobank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> Each is believed to have about $ 5 billion in assets. Because the ruble is not a convertible currency, the Soviets must use Western money in order to pay for goods imported from non-communist trading parters. As with other currency speculators, the Soviets like to move their holdings into the currency that is worth the most at any given time. They are said to favor the Swiss franc, although they also have deposits and trading accounts denominated in dollars, British pounds, West German marks and Japanese yen. `` They used to be into wild speculation, but they're more careful now,'' said <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Vanous </PERSON>, a Soviet expert at <ORGANIZATION> Planecon </ORGANIZATION>, a Washington-based consulting and information concern that studies the centrally planned economies of the Soviet bloc. A few years ago, for example, Soviet traders attempted to push down the value of the Swiss franc by dumping $ 50 million worth of francs in 20 separate orders throughout <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, assuming dealers would not be able to communicate fast enough about who was selling. The Soviets were wrong, losing money and respect. `` It really caused a lot of bad blood,'' <PERSON> Vanous </PERSON> said. `` You do this to someone in the foreign-exchange market, and the next time they deal with you they're extra careful.'' Some traders have privately accused the Soviets of eavesdropping on international telephone lines for advance word on central bank coordination and intervention, which often moves a currency sharply. The <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> Norodny bank, for example, is believed to have once made huge profits on marks it bought just before the mark soared in value after the West German <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> made a surprise policy shift. That change resulted from a telephone conversation hours earlier between aides from the <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, and according to one widely circulated story the Soviets learned about it through a wiretap. On the other hand, the Soviets can show remarkable naivete about economic trends that hurt their currency holdings. They were active buyers of dollars just before the currency tumbled because of a coordination agreement by the leading Western democracies and the collapse of oil prices a few years ago. `` Generally they are savvy in the short run, but they do n't do too well in the long run,'' said <PERSON> Vanous </PERSON>. `` They are miserable in making forecasts. They do n't have the trained people, the information, and keep making judgments based on their own behavior.''
