<HEAD>Former NY Fed Member Indicted For Insider Trading</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A former president of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jersey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> has been accused of leaking highly secret <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> interest rate figures to a now-bankrupt brokerage firm seeking a jump on the securities market. An indictment returned here Thursday charged <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> A </PERSON>. Rough with insider trading while a member of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, part of the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s regional network, from 1982 to 1984. Rough, 49, of <LOCATION> Layton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, received $ 47,000 in interest-deferred loans from the now-defunct <PERSON> Bevill </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Bresler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Schulman </PERSON> investment firm in exchange for the information, the indictment charged. Rough is accused of relaying the data by telephone from his executive suite at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sussex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> and once from the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s boardroom just after a meeting, prosecutors told a news conference. <PERSON> Bevill </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bresler </PERSON> made millions of dollars in government securities trades based on Rough's advance word about decisions made by the national <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> on the discount rate and on recommendations made by the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> about the discount rate, the indictment said. Changes in the discount rate, the interest charged by the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> on loans to banks, can have a strong impact on financial markets. Rough's attorney, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Himmel </PERSON>, would not comment in detail but said: `` Mr. Rough is going to enter a plea of not guilty and vigorously contest the charges.'' Rough's home telephone number is unlisted and he could not be reached for comment. He resigned earlier this year as president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sussex </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Branchville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> is one of 12 regional banks in the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION>, all of which make recommendations every two weeks on whether the discount rate should be changed. The national <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> has the final say in setting the rate. Word that discount rate information was leaked surfaced in April 1987 during a trial stemming from the collapse of <PERSON> Bevill </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bresler </PERSON>, prompting the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> to tighten its rules on disclosing the discount rate. The allegations came to light during the trial of <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schulman </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bevill </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bresler </PERSON>'s president, on charges stemming from the $ 144 million collapse of the <ORGANIZATION> Livingston </ORGANIZATION>, N.J.-based firm in April 1985. Three other principals who pleaded guilty in the firm's collapse in exchange for their cooperation testified about Rough's allegedly passing on the <PERSON> Schulman </PERSON>, a long-time friend of Rough's, is serving an 8-year sentence for securities violations. <PERSON> Schulman </PERSON> testified that Rough approached him for the $ 47,000 in loans to buy a chunk of stock in the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sussex </ORGANIZATION>. Rough faces 29 years in prison if convicted on all counts, said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Alito </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr </PERSON>. Rough was charged with conspiracy to commit wire and securities fraud, two counts of bank fraud, one count each of wire fraud and securities fraud and two counts of making false statements to banks. No arraignment date has been set. <PERSON> Alito </PERSON> said <PERSON> Rough </PERSON> violated a position of `` great power, trust and responsibility,'' and hoped the case would serve as a warning to other would-be insider-traders of interest rate data. `` He abused that office in a very shocking and outrageous manner,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> officials have called the discount rate one of their most closely guarded secrets. The rate is widely regarded as an indicator of the direction in which the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> is seeking to push interest rates, which affect the prices of bonds. Federal authorities were told by <PERSON> Bevill </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bresler </PERSON> principals of the allegations against Rough during interviews shortly after the firm's collapse. After the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> learned of them, it stopped telling regional federal reserves of its decision on the discount rate earlier in the day than when it was announced publicly, said <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakstansky </PERSON>. The indictment took so long because of the complex process of examining <PERSON> Bevill </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bresler </PERSON>'s brokerage operations, <PERSON> Alito </PERSON> said. He said the case was the first insider-trading scheme involving the discount rate, and the first against a sitting member of a federal reserve bank. Rough sat on the board as a representative of small banks in the regional <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s district.
