<FIRST>a f BC-TickerTalk Adv12   12-09 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ticker Talk, Adv 12,0619</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 12</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday Dec. 12</NOTE>
<HEAD>Hunting For Gold in Wall Street's Scrap Heap</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The prime time is at hand for a special brand of holiday shopping that has become a tradition of sorts on Wall Street. Stock analysts and traders are busily combing the markets for issues trading at or near their lowest levels of the year. The idea is to buy these stocks while they are artificially depressed by yearend sell orders _ from individual investors looking for tax writeoffs and from institutions clearing the losers out of their portfolios before they make yearend reports to clients. Once the pressure of this selling is removed with the arrival of the new year, the reasoning goes, these stocks stand a good chance of rebounding, even if the financial affairs of the companies involved do n't change much. In his annual Stock Trader's Almanac, investment adviser <PERSON> Yale </PERSON> <PERSON> Hirsch </PERSON> describes the list of stocks trading at new 52-week lows around Dec. 15 as a menu for `` the only free lunch on Wall Street.'' For most of the time in the past 15 years, according to <PERSON> Hirsch </PERSON>'s research, the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> issues at new lows on Dec. 15 outperformed the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> composite index through the following Feb. 15 Last winter, for example, the 23 new lows posted an aggregate gain of 13.2 percent over the two-month period, compared to a 6.8 percent rise for the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> index. Occasionally, however, the `` free lunch'' is more famine than feast. The four new lows at mid-December 1985, which included three energy-related issues, suffered an overall loss of 22.5 percent by the next Feb. 15 as oil prices nosedived. In addition, small investors armed with limited capital face problems turning this historical trend into a workable trading strategy. Brokerage commissions take their considerable toll. And if a trader does n't have enough money to buy a diversified package of the stocks at new lows, which ones to pick? The December bargain hunt does dovetail nicely with a phenomenon known as the `` January effect'' that has been widely analyzed in academic studies and at least one book. This research has documented a tendency for stocks, especially those of smaller companies, to show unusual strength in the first few weeks of the year. The only trouble with the January effect, analysts say, is the very recognition it has received. Once market patterns become well known, they often quickly change as traders try to capitalize on them. Thus the suspicion among a good many Wall Streeters that the January effect will soon be negated, or at least moved into December. Whether or not they prove to be `` bargains,'' many of the lists of depressed stocks being published these days contain a surprising number of big names. For example, at <ORGANIZATION> Oppenheimer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, analysts <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinger </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Metz </PERSON> ran a computer screen of stocks with market values of at least $ 50 million, priced at no more than 10 percent above their 52-week lows, and carrying price-earnings multiples of no more than 10. The names that turned up included <ORGANIZATION> Digital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equipment </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Instruments </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> NCR </ORGANIZATION> and several technology issues that once ranked as leading glamour stocks. Blue-chip industrial companies? How about <ORGANIZATION> DuPont </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Weyerhaueser </PERSON>, for starters. `` No investment decision is warranted on the basis of these figures alone,'' <PERSON> Weinger </PERSON> and <PERSON> Metz </PERSON> cautioned. For a further observation, they added: `` It is interesting to note how many stocks are still down sharply'' in the aftermath of the October 1987 crash.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday Dec 12</NOTE>
