<HEAD>EEC Official Says Hormone Ban Will Go Into Effect</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Trade Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> said Friday that a ban on the imports of hormone-treated meat from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will go into effect next month. The ban, implementation of which was postponed for one year at the request of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, could provoke a trade war with <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Nicolas </PERSON> <PERSON> Wegter </PERSON> also said the 12-nation EEC only would agree to international arbitration of the dispute with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> if consumer-related arguments as well as scientific ones are taken into account. The ban legislated by the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>, which goes into effect Jan. 1, would affect $ 170 million of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> meat exports. This does not include about $ 72 million of horsemeat, which is not treated with hormones. EEC and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> negotiators were expected to have an opportunity to discuss possible solutions to the dispute when they met here this week for a ministerial conference of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade. But a U.S.-EEC clash over support for farmers prevented the discussion from taking place. The matter will also not be taken up at a bilateral meeting of ministers taking place in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> Friday because the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> agriculture negotiators had to stay in <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION> longer than expected and did not get to <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> in time. `` We do n't care what the Americans want for their consumers,'' said <PERSON> Wegter </PERSON>. `` Our legislation goes into effect and we will apply it.'' A <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> investigation of reports that European farmers violate the legislation and treat their animals with hormones will not affect implementation of the ban, he said. The council of the <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION>, which oversees implementation of the 1947 treaty regulating world trade, is scheduled to meet Dec. 20 to consider a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> request for establishing an arbitration pnel. <PERSON> Wegter </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> would only accept the arbitration panel if it `` does n't rely just on scientific arguments but also on consumer-related and other arguments.'' He said most <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> members already had legislated bans on hormone-treated meat, `` and they think it's good for their consumers.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> insists that hormones used on animals do not leave residues that are harmful to humans. Some European scientists have concurred, while others have argued that the hormones can cause cancer. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> could retaliate against the meat ban with one of its own against European meat exports, which consist mostly of high quality items like Danish ham.
