<FIRST>u f PM-TradeTalks-Japan 1stLd-Writethru   12-09 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Trade Talks-Japan, 1st Ld-Writethru,0502</SECOND>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with European official saying Japan was silent on
agriculture talks, edits throughout</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Assochated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trade Representative <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> declared himself satisfied with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s role in internatonal trade talks here and said he would reject a petition by American farmers to demand access to the Japanese rice market. But a spokesman for the 12-nation <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Nicolas </PERSON> <PERSON> Wegter </PERSON>, said Friday that `` the Japanese did n't say one word the entire week about agriculture.'' <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> had told reporters that the Japanese delegation to the ministeral meeting of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade `` performed superbly.'' `` They handled themselves skillfully,'' he added. `` It was a first class performance.'' <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the world's largest net importer of agricultural products, sat in on six days of talks between the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the world's leading farm exporters. `` I did n't hear the translators translate one word from Japanese into agriculture,'' <PERSON> Wegter </PERSON> told reporters. The divergence of views reflected attempts by the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to curry <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s favor in their battle over agricultural subsidies. <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON>, asked whether he would accept a petition by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Millers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, responded, `` I will not.'' Several weeks ago <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> rejected a petition by the American rice producers' group which called on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government to investigate whether <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is employing unfair trade practices in refusing to open its rice market to imports. In turning down the petition, <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said he hoped the rice question would be resolved in <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION> and if not the farmers could resubmit their appeal. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s ruling <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, concerned with the veiled threat of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> pressure, sent a delegation to <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION> to make sure the foreign ministry negotiators did not cave in to demands on the rice issue. But much to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s relief, the subject was virtually not mentioned during the six days of talks, which were dominated by the U.S.-EEC clash on farm supports. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is seeking farm subsidy elimination, while the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> is only willing to cut down the supports. The talks ended in stalemate. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> said it did not take sides in the clash. `` Our position is that there is no point in making decisions until they settle,'' said <PERSON> Mutsuyoshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Nishimura </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s director of foreign press relations. <PERSON> Nishimura </PERSON> said that whatever the outcome, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s prime concern is the protection of its rice market against foreign imports. The administration appears content to allow the rice issue to rest as long as <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> leaves it on the table for future negotiations. Japanese rice is about four times more expensive than <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> rice, but <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is insistent on complete self-reliance in production of the staple crop. The Rice Millers were demanding a quota of up to 2.5 percent of the Japanese market the first year, which would rise to 10 percent in the fourth year.
