<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two men have been charged with attempted extortion in a series of death threat letters sent to prominent <LOCATION> Antelope </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> citizens. Although the two unemployed aerospace workers are suspected of sending 265 computer-printed threats, they were charged with only 10 specific acts to simplify the case, Deputy District Attorney <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooley </PERSON> said Thursday. `` Many of the letters were identical,'' said <PERSON> Cooley </PERSON>, but he noted that the text of each letter was `` customized'' to include personal information about the intended victims. Roman <PERSON> Stephan </PERSON> <PERSON> Makuch </PERSON>, 27, and <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Mathew </PERSON> <PERSON> Faroni </PERSON>, 26, were arrested in <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> on Thanksgiving Day and waived extradition. Letters attached to the complaint began with an obscenity and a death threat. The writers then demanded specific amounts of cash as high as $ 600,000 with instructions for its delivery. They also gave gruesome details of how victims would be killed, and threatened harm to children, spouses and relatives of the letter recipients, <PERSON> Cooley </PERSON> said. Those targeted by the letter writers, he said, were all `` substantial people'' including a former city manager of <LOCATION> Lancaster </LOCATION>, lawyers, bank vice presidents, doctors, dentists, accountants and real estate agents. None of them paid any money, he said. The letters, received Nov. 2-3, told some recipients to take a citizens band radio to <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> and tune in a specific channel for instructions on where to deliver money. <PERSON> Cooley </PERSON> said a search of a <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> apartment occupied by <PERSON> Makuch </PERSON> and <PERSON> Faroni </PERSON> and a nearby storage facility turned up computer, printers and computer discs, a handgun and several CB radios. He said acquaintances said about the pair: `` They could be characterized as being a couple of oddballs, misfits.'' <PERSON> Cooley </PERSON> added, `` there is some indication there may be other people involved.'' <PERSON> Makuch </PERSON> and <PERSON> Faroni </PERSON> were unemployed but had worked previously on the assembly line at <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Palmdale </LOCATION> plant on the B-1B bomber project, <PERSON> Cooley </PERSON> said. Both were charged with conspiracy to commit extortion, attempted extortion and sending threatening letters for extortion purposes. If convicted, <PERSON> Cooley </PERSON> said they could draw maximum sentences of six years in prison.
