<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 2203EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv12   12-09 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 12,0590</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv12</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Monday, Dec. 12</NOTE>
<HEAD>The Year It Didn't Happen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the next few weeks the media will attempt to wrap up the economic year, and one of their themes is likely to be that 1988 was the year when it did n't happen. So much did n't happen that was expected to happen _ a secondary shock wave in the stock market and a recession, for instance _ that it carries a message for 1989. That message: Do n't place too much faith in the seers, because they really do n't put all that faith in themselves. Many of the stock market doomsayers, for example, reversed themselves last summer and put their bets on stocks. Another school of economic sages based their forecast of recession on the assumption that an expansion that had already gone on for five years would have to stop for breath. Instead, the expansion merely slowed and inhaled. Now, one year later, these seers are expressing the identical doubts they had in 1987, and for the very same reasons. It is a no-lose situation, because a recession that does n't come can be explained away as unexpectedly good news. And eventually, if not now, they will be right; they'll let you know about it. Interest rates rose, but they did n't go through the roof. Prices did n't run away. Housing did n't collapse. Cars had a good year. The jobless rate continued to fall. Contrary to many forecasts, the trade and budget deficits narrowed, too. The fact that these dire forecasts did n't materialize does n't mean it was a dull year It was n't a dull year, but the things that made it exciting and unusual had very little to do with the foresight of the seers. Do you recall any of them telling you that corporate takeovers would reach such a frantic pace? Did anyone even conceive of a company the size of <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> being auctioned off? It is therefore wise in reviewing the forecasts to remember that much of it is a game; when you win you get up on the roof and shout and demonstrate, and when you're wrong you remain in your study and guard your quiet dignity. Nothing can stop the forecasts; they'll be made, if only for publicity purposes. The future, oddly, is an attractive place, largely because it is the great unknown. Though it is a dark mystery, the future is where much of the investment community seeks to reside. You make money by anticipating, by getting in on things early, by beating others, by buying before the news gets around. And so there will be forecasts. Stock market seers make them to impress customers. Scholars sometimes make them because of conviction, or probably to sell books. Market letter writers make them because forecasts excite interest. But evidence that very few people really can foresee the future, at least with any tiny degree of consistency, lies in the consensus forecast, about which you will be reading plenty. The consensus forecast is the median forecast. It is the middle range between extremes. The consensus is often right on the mark, correctly estimating such items as inflation, interest rates and gross national product. And when the consensus is on the mark it means, by definition, that most of the forecasts it is made of are not on the mark.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Monday Dec. 12</NOTE>
</DOC>
