<HEAD>Spain Approves Railway System Overhaul</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> on Friday adopted <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s standard width for railroad tracks, a step that will allow trains to roll directly into western <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> for the first time since track was laid 133 years ago. The move clears the way for completion of high-speed train links with <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> by 1992, when <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> hosts the Summer Olympics and celebrates the 500th anniversary of <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Columbus </PERSON>' discovery of the New World. The government next week is expected to award a major contract to build <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s first high-speed train system. French, West German and Japanese firms are bidding for the deal. The first phase of the changeover to the narrower European tracks would permit construction of a high-speed line from <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bou </LOCATION> on <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s northern border with <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Barcelona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Seville </LOCATION>. By the turn of the century, the 5.5-foot-wide Spanish and <LOCATION> Portuguese </LOCATION> tracks would be replaced with 4.7-foot-wide track used in 10 other European Economic Community nations. Transport Minister <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Barrionuevo </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> France-to-Seville </LOCATION> line should be ready by the opening of <LOCATION> Seville </LOCATION>'s World Expo in spring 1992 to commemorate the <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION> anniversary and the 1992 <LOCATION> Barcelona </LOCATION> Summer Olympics. The government also ordered the state rail company, <ORGANIZATION> RENFE </ORGANIZATION>, to study replacing the rest of the country's 7,887 miles of rail track by 2001. It is widely believed that <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> railways were given a narrower gauge than the rest of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> when first built in 1855 to make a military invasion of the <LOCATION> Iberian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> peninsula </LOCATION> more difficult. Engineers maintained that a wider gauge was necessary to accommodate locomotives that carried trains across <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s mountainous terrain Now, wheels on railway cars from <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> must be changed or modified at the <LOCATION> Spanish-French </LOCATION> border.
