<FIRST>r f AM-EEC-Hormones-Shultz     12-09 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-EEC-Hormones-Shultz,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shultz Says U.S. Right In Meat Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said Friday that `` we're right'' in opposing the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>'s planned ban on hormone-treated meat from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> told reporters the meat the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> wants to send to European buyers `` is very acceptable.'' `` There is no health problem involved as we see it,'' he said after meeting with officials of the 12-nation Common Market trade bloc. In <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Nico </PERSON> <PERSON> Wegter </PERSON>, said the ban would take effect Jan. 1 as scheduled. `` We do n't care what the Americans want for their consumers,'' <PERSON> Wegter </PERSON> said. `` Our legislation goes into effect, and we will apply it.'' The <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> wants to ban for health reasons all meat from animals treated with growth hormones. Late last year, it agreed to delay implementation of the prohibition until 1989. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had threatened to take retaliatory action against the ban. It maintains that the use of hormones to fatten animals, a common practice among American farmers, is not a health risk. An estimated $ 170 million in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> meat exports would be affected by the ban. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said the value of meat exports to the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> is small compared to this year's estimated $ 166 billion two-way trade between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the trading bloc. But, he said, `` It's large to the people involved.'' He acknowledged a difference of opinion with the community, but said, `` We think we're right.'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> met with <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Delors </PERSON> and other top trade officials. The talks were held as international trade negotiations in <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION> were postponed for four months over a stalemate between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the Common Market over phasing out agricultural subsidies. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is pressing <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> to agree to eliminate subsidies it claims distort international trade by supporting cut-rate exports and restricting imports. The Europeans argue they have taken steps to control farm spending and could only agree to reduce the subsidies _ not scrap them altogether. `` There is a general recognition that the system of subsidies to agriculture has got itself structured wrong and is altogether too costly,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said. He said the subsidies cost the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and the Common Market an estimated $ 200 billion a year. `` There are big stakes involved, economic stakes and political stakes, and that's the reason why people are so intense about it,'' he said. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>'s discussions concluded a two-day trip to <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> primarily for a meeting with other foreign ministers of the 16-nation <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>.
