<HEAD>Is the Yield Curve Changing Course?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the world of credit, `` short'' is most definitely in fashion these days, at least from an investor's standpoint Yields on some bills and notes, particularly in the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> market, have nearly equaled or surpassed those on longer maturing bonds more so now than at any other time this year. That makes it far more sensible to hold onto the shorter securities. Usually it's the other way around. Long-term rates often are significantly higher to compensate investors for their increased risk. For instance, it's more likely that someone will renege on a 30-year debt than on one lasting three months. There's also increased risk of higher interest rates, which depress a bond's price, and higher inflation, which reduce its real value But now the so-called yield curve, which illustrates the difference between short - and long-term interest rates, appears to be changing Normally in an upward, or `` J'' position, the curve, which has been flat for most of the year, looks close to inverting. By midday Friday, the yield on the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s bellwether 30-year bond stood at 8.96 percent, lower than the yields of all other bonds and notes of lesser maturities. The 20-year bond was yielding 9.02 percent; the 10-year, 9.01 percent; the four-year, 9.00 percent; and the two-year, 8.99 percent. Treasury bill yields remained a bit lower, however. A quick measure of the curve is the relationship between the three-month bill and the 30-year bond. By Friday afternoon the long bond was 0.79 percentage points higher than the bill. The gap, though, was closing in on the one-year bill, which was yielding 8.90 percent. When the yield curve is in a positive, upward steep the long bond is usually between 1 -LCB- - to 2 percentage points higher in yield. The yield curve theoretically should reflect the expectations of borrowers and investors. One that ascends steeply indicates that the markets expect interest rates and inflation to rise; it also portrays `` easy'' money. The last time the curve inverted was around 1981. The stock market fell into a slump as a result and the nation headed into a recession. Market watchers are n't sure what the current movement of rates means. <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldinger </PERSON>, a principal at the <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, investment banking firm <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said he expects the yield curve to continue to invert but that the economy should n't suffer as a result `` What it -LRB- the inversion -RRB- really means is inflation expectations in this country continue to be reduced as the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> has done a good job of tightening'' credit, <PERSON> Goldinger </PERSON> said. `` This is nothing unusual. We have an inverted yield curve in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>,'' he explained. `` The central banks of this world really pay attention in focusing in on inflation fears.'' <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> B. Front, an economist at the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Stein </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farnham </ORGANIZATION>, predicted that rates might be heading lower soon because the economy is showing signs of slowing down. While short-term rates certainly are attractive now _ not just in <LOCATION> Treasuries </LOCATION>, but in things like certificates of deposits or money market accounts _ Front says he's gradually sinking his money into longer-maturing securities. `` Our own guess is that we're fairly close to a peak in short-term rates. We could see a decline in rates before the end of the first quarter,'' Front said. If that happens, then bond prices will head higher. `` We do n't think we'll have a repeat of the last few cycles where you had a sharply inverted yield curve,'' Front said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Dec. 10-11</NOTE>
