 <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. PLC and <ORGANIZATION> Siemens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AG </ORGANIZATION> said Friday they would delay their 1.7 billion-pound, or $ 3.1 billion, joint bid for the British electronics firm <ORGANIZATION> Plessey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. PLC pending a high court hearing late next <ORGANIZATION> Plessey </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday obtained a preliminary injunction from the High Court blocking the offer before a full court hearing on whether the bid infringes on the anti-competition provisions of the Treaty of <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Plessey </ORGANIZATION> said the injunction was dropped by the court on Friday after <ORGANIZATION> GEC </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Siemens </ORGANIZATION> pledged not to pursue their bid before the full hearing. The matter is now likely to come before the court next Thursday and Friday, <ORGANIZATION> Plessey </ORGANIZATION> said. <ORGANIZATION> GEC </ORGANIZATION>, a British company, which is not related to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> company of the same name, said it intends to contest <ORGANIZATION> Plessey </ORGANIZATION>'s arguments. <ORGANIZATION> Siemens </ORGANIZATION> is a West German concern. <ORGANIZATION> Plessey </ORGANIZATION> argued that the GEC-Siemens bid is anti-competitive and illegal and allegedly contravenes the anti-trust provisions of the Treaty of <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>'s founding charter. The <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION> commission is also investigating the bid, but has not yet announced its decision.
