<HEAD>Deficit Panel Cancels Meeting After Judge Says It Must Be Public</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A bipartisan commission appointed to study ways to reduce the federal budget deficit Friday canceled its next meeting after a judge barred the panel from closing the proceedings to the public. The decision by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Joyce </PERSON> <PERSON> Hens </PERSON> <PERSON> Green </PERSON> prompted the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> to cancel Monday's meeting at which it was to review budget options and discuss which economic assumptions would be used to make recommendations for deficit reduction. `` It is evident in this case that the public has the right to know the issues at discussion as they develop at the December 12 meeting,'' <PERSON> Green </PERSON> ruled in granting a temporary restraining order barring a closed proceeding. `` The meeting is canceled,'' commission spokesman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hildreth </PERSON> said following Green's decision. `` We were challenged and we will abide by the court. Where we will go from here, we simply do n't know. The commission has no other scheduled meetings this month and had only discussed tentative dates for discussions in January, <PERSON> Hildreth </PERSON> said. The judge ruled that news organizations that brought the case would likely ultimately be able to prove that closed meetings violate the Federal Advisory Commission Act and the Sunshine Act. `` The commission's insistence on shielding the debate as to budget options from public scrutiny directly contravenes the law,'' <PERSON> Green </PERSON> wrote in an opinion. `` It chops the core of our democratic society: open robust, unvarnished public debate illuminating pressing issues, concerns and policies that affect the lives of all citizens,'' she said. The judge rejected the commission's arguments that because the panel's members were so prestigious, their public discussions of various economic options could wreak havoc with the financial markets. `` The expressions to be presented by these officials are no different than the plethora of economic assessments and predictions -LRB- some optimistic, some grave -RRB- that inundate the public daily,'' <PERSON> Green </PERSON> said. While such discussion may result in speculation on financial markets, the effect `` must be balanced against the open society and unfettered public debate on important national issues upon which our democracy is founded,'' the judge said. A closed meeting would more likely encourage speculation, he said, adding: `` Fear flourishes when the process is shrouded in a cloak of secrecy and the swiftest transport to speculation is fear.'' The lawsuit challenging the closed meeting was filed by <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, The Wall Street Journal, the <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION>, which publishes financial newsletters, and <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Wildstrom </PERSON>, an editor for Business Week. Public Citizen, a consumer organization founded by <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Nader </PERSON>, represented the news organizations and also joined in the case. In a statement, <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizen </ORGANIZATION>'s president, <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Claybrook </PERSON>, said: `` The idea that the members of this commission are too prestigious to air their views in public is outrageous, and an affront to our open system of government.''
