<FIRST>u f AM-NewSecurity Bjt   12-09 0857</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-New Security, Bjt,0884</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wall Street, Investors Weigh Unbundled Stock Units</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Wall Street's latest financial product, the unbundled stock unit, is being touted as a way for top-quality companies to unlock the hidden values in their shares without having to dismantle the company. But the proposal has also unleashed a torrent of questions from investors and money managers trying to figure if there is anything in it for them. <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which developed the proposal embraced by four major companies earlier this week, has created a product that splits a stock into three components _ a 30-year bond, a preferred stock and a stock appreciation certificate. <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Sara </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Pfizer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> have filed documents with the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> to offer their shareholders a chance to swap up to $ 5.6 billion in stock for new securities. While the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> reviews the filings, money managers are trying to figure how the new securities will work, what they will be worth and whether there will be be enough of them that there will be a ready buyer when a holder wants to sell. While their inventors say they were not intended as a takeover defense, some investors say they may have that effect. Critics say the tax savings for issuers inherent in the plans may invite congressional scrutiny. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>, a professional investor and professor of finance at <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s graduate school of business, said the new securities are `` a waste of time ... I do n't see what's in it for most people.'' `` The question you have to ask yourself is do we really need another piece of paper to maintain our capital system,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Dreman </PERSON>, director of a money management firm that bears his name. But <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallatin </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> executive who oversaw the invention of unbundled stock units, said they will be useful for major companies with credit ratings strong enough to absorb some modest increases in debt. He said they are designed to highlight the three reasons people buy stock _ the chance for a price increase, the dividend and the possibility that the dividend will be raised. The 30-year bond will pay interest equal to the current annual dividend. The preferred stock would pay any increase over the next 30 years in the current level of the dividend. The stock appreciation certificate would entitle the holder to buy a share of the company's stock in 30 years for a pre-set price expected to be slightly higher than the face value of the bond. Investors making the swap would be protected against a dividend reduction, since the dividend would become a fixed interest payment. But some investment managers wonder how liquid the market for the new securities will be. `` You'll only be able to determine that when they come out,'' said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Minter </PERSON>, a partner in the investment advisory firm <ORGANIZATION> Comstock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Gallatin </LOCATION> conceded that since the exchange of stock for an unbundled unit would be taxable, the units should appeal mainly to tax-exempt institutions such as pension funds. Those making the exchange would also give up their voting rights, a development that some analysts suspect management would like. `` If you remove 20 percent of the stock from the market, you could end up with a higher percentage in friendly hands,'' said <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Heebner </PERSON>, a portfolio manager at <ORGANIZATION> Loomis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sayles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. From the issuer's standpoint, the security may be especially attractive to companies that feel undervalued, have little debt and want to avoid the heavy borrowing that would be needed to buy back stock for cash. This is particularly attractive at a time when many American managers see other companies succumbing to takeovers at prices far in excess of market values. The publisher <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> foodmaker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and food and tobacco giant <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> have all fallen prey in recent months to takeover offers at a huge premiums to their stock prices. The swaps would have a mixed financial impact on an issuer, however. On the one hand, the company loses the flexibility of being able to reduce its costs in bad times. It can always cut a dividend but not interest payments. But the company would save on taxes since interest payments are deductible while dividends are not. `` This plays into the hands of those in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> who say debt has become a device for avoiding taxes,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Ullman </PERSON>, trustee of <ORGANIZATION> Batterymarch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION>. A staffer on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, speaking on condition that he not be identified by name, said the panel has taken no position on whether to investigate the uses of the unbundled stock unit, and said whether it does so may depend on how many companies use it. The one clear winner in all this, investment managers say, will be the underwriters who get a fee for handling the exchanges and the brokers who will get commissions on executing trades involving all of the new products. `` It is a reflection of the battered shape of Wall Street,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Batterymarch </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Ullman </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
