<FIRST>u f AM-TradeTalks Bjt   12-09 0665</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trade Talks, Bjt,0686</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trade Talks End With Only Tentative Gains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 World trade talks ended inconclusively Friday, with tentative gains in many areas but no sign of compromise on the critical issue of farm supports. `` I suppose we could say it's a semi-success,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Crosbie </PERSON>, minister of international trade for host <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. Trade ministers agreed to postpone final action until the first week in April, hoping a way will be found in the meantime to break a deadlock between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> over agriculture. Top officials from 103 nations _ including 90 trade ministers _ came to <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION> to prod along the four-year <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> Round of free-trade talks under the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade. This is the most ambitious round of free-trade talks since formation of the <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> after World War II, and negotiators are discovering deep sensitivities over agriculture, which had been largely exempted from scrutiny until now. The four-month delay in the so-called midterm review of the <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Round </LOCATION> meant that progress was frozen in 11 areas of tentative agreement, including important ones such as freeing trade in services and monitoring nations' trade policies. <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunkel </PERSON>, the director general of the <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION>, will seek to bridge differences over the next four months in the four remaining areas: agriculture, protection of intellectual property, textile tariffs and quotas, and escape clauses from <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> rules. <PERSON> Dunkel </PERSON> expressed optimism that he could persuade the American and <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> negotiators to yield by appealing to their guilty consciences over the impasse on agriculture. `` When people have bad conscience it's a good start to make a deal,'' he said in a news conference. The farm deadlock had threatened to derail the entire negotiations because some nations that depend on farm exports had warned they would withhold approval of the other agreements unless they got some progress on agriculture. The nations that demanded progress in all areas included <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> demanded a commitment by all nations to the eventual elimination of trade-distorting farm subsidies and barriers, while the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> said it was willing to cut but not eliminate such programs. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> said it would not discuss short-term measures until it got a commitment on the long-term goal, while the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> said it would not discuss a long-term goal until short-term measures had been agreed upon. These were some of the tentative accords reached in <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION>, subject to approval in April: _ Import tariffs on most goods would be cut by at least the 30 percent achieved in the last <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> round, which ended in 1979. The significance of tariff cuts has diminished somewhat along with the rise in non-tariff barriers. _ Trade in services would be liberalized, although developing nations would be allowed to give their service industries some kind of extra protection. Sectors to be covered would be decided by May 1989. _ To speed up settlement of disputes, all <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> reports on disputes would have to be completed within 15 months unless the parties agreed to an extension. _ The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would be permitted to take trade retaliation outside the <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> rules even if a <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> proceeding on its complaint was under way. _ The legality of countries' trade policies would be reviewed every two years for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> countries; every four years for 16 other countries; and as needed for all other <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> members. _ The <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION>'s director general would be instructed to seek closer ties to the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> and report back by September 1989. _ Developed countries would lower barriers to imports of tropical products such as coffee, bananas and rubber from developing nations. The <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> said Friday it would go ahead with its concessions on tropical products and eliminate tariffs on imports from some of the world's poorest countries without waiting for the April meeting.
</TEXT>
