<HEAD>Finance Minister Biggest Casualty Yet of Insider Scandal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IRENE M. KUNII</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Finance Minister <PERSON> Kiichi </PERSON> <PERSON> Miyazawa </PERSON> resigned Friday, the highest-ranking government official to quit in the aftermath of an insider trading scandal, while critics intensified demands for a full-scale probe of the share purchases by politicians. <PERSON> Miyazawa </PERSON> said he was resigning as finance minister and deputy premier to take responsibility for conflicting statements in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> regarding his involvement in questionable purchases of stock of the real estate firm <ORGANIZATION> Recruit-Cosmos </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` My explanations were n't sufficient and I am taking responsibility,'' <PERSON> Miyazawa </PERSON> told reporters after he informed Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> he was quitting. He also said he hoped his resignation would facilitate passage of a major tax reform package through the Parliament. `` Accomplishing tax reform is my mission,'' <PERSON> Miyazawa </PERSON> said. `` It does n't matter what happens to me.'' <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>, who is expected to announce a Cabinet shuffle in the next few weeks, told reporters later that he would assume the finance portfolio. He refused to comment, however, on how long he would hold that reponsibility. More than a dozen leading politicians, including <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> and former Prime Minister <PERSON> Yasuhiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Nakasone </PERSON>, have been linked to the stock profiteering deal devised by businessman <PERSON> Hiromasa </PERSON> <PERSON> Ezoe </PERSON>, founder of the information conglomerate <ORGANIZATION> Recruit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Ezoe </PERSON> reportedly offered certain individuals the opportunity to purchase bargain-priced shares in <LOCATION> Recruit-Cosmos </LOCATION>, a Recruit affiliate, prior to their over-the-counter listing in October 1986 Shortly after the shares were offered for public trading, their value rose sharply and earned large profits for holders, many of whom were also provided with interest-free financing to buy the shares. Opposition leaders spearheading a probe of the stock deal _ dubbed Recruit-gate as a parallel to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Watergate scandal _ have charged that politicians were offered the lucrative shares in return for political favor. <PERSON> Miyazawa </PERSON> himself came under fire after delivering several conflicting reports regarding his former secretary's role in the incident. He initially testified to a parliamentary committee investigating the scandal that a third party, a friend of his former secretary, purchased 10,000 <ORGANIZATION> Recruit-Cosmos </ORGANIZATION> shares and only borrowed the name of `` Miyazawa.'' He later admitted his ex-secretary actually paid 30 million yen, or about $ 246,000, for the shares in September 1986 and sold them for 52.7 million yen or $ 431,000 less than a month later after they were listed without the finance minister's knowledge. <PERSON> Miyazawa </PERSON> also insisted the stock purchase was not financed by a Recruit-linked financial institution but refused to show bank documents to back up his argument. <PERSON> Miyazawa </PERSON> is the largest casualty to date in the five-month-old scandal that has shaken public confidence in <LOCATION> Takeshita </LOCATION> government. Public support for <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>'s government dropped to 18 percent from 30 percent when he assumed office a year ago, according to a survey released Friday by the mass-circulation newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Mainichi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shimbun </ORGANIZATION>. The leading opposition <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and other critics said <PERSON> Miyazawa </PERSON>'s resignation was overdue but renewed demands for a stepped-up investigation of the scandal. The <ORGANIZATION> Asahi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shimbun </ORGANIZATION>, a leading liberal daily, said it was time for <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> to heed the opinion polls and `` listen to the voice of the people'' who want the Recruit affair cleared up.
