<HEAD>Judge Puts Commission Action Against Hunts On Hold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankruptcy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> judge has approved a request to forestall action by the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> against two of the Hunt brothers of <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> while they work out Chapter 11 reorganization settlements. `` We had an order -LRB- that -RRB- enjoined the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> from proceedings until other matters are resolved,'' said Judge <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Abramson </PERSON> of his 36-page opinion handed down Thursday in the cases of <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON> and <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Bunker </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> complaint claims the two <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> businessmen, who filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection in September, and others manipulated the price of silver futures between fall 1979 and March 1980. Silver prices collapsed to $ 10 an ounce on March 27, 1980, after previously hitting a high of $ 52 an ounce. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitaker </PERSON>, vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Hunt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> and a spokesman for the brothers, said the Hunts are pleased with <PERSON> Abramson </PERSON>'s decision. `` Our ongoing intent is still intact _ that is to get all these proceedings into one forum,'' he said. <PERSON> Whitaker </PERSON> estimated it could be 12 to 14 months before the bankruptcy court matters are resolved. Attorneys for the Hunts filed statements of financial affairs and schedules of assets and liabilities in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankruptcy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> last month. Now creditors have until mid-January to file claims with the court, <PERSON> Whitaker </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Angela </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tese </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> bankruptcy attorney whose firm <ORGANIZATION> Cole </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Deitz </PERSON> has been observing the Hunt case, said <PERSON> Abramson </PERSON>'s decision means damages and claims against the brothers take precedence over fines and penalties that might be imposed. `` The decision of the bankruptcy court judge is not an unusual one at all,'' Ms. <PERSON> Tese </PERSON> said. `` It's in keeping with the spirit of the bankruptcy code.'' She said the decision apparently does not mean the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> will drop its civil complaint against the Hunts. `` It's possible that they will proceed at some later date,'' she said. The <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> general counsel, who is handling the case, did not immediately return telephone calls to The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> on Friday. In September, administrative law Judge <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shipe </PERSON> ruled that the Hunts' personal bankruptcy court filings did not automatically block the government's case against the brothers. The <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION>'s complaint is the biggest market manipulation case ever filed by the commission. If the Hunts lose, they could face fines of $ 100,000 for each violation of federal commodity laws and be premanently banned from trading in all futures markets. <PERSON> Whitaker </PERSON> also said <PERSON> Abramson </PERSON>'s ruling also means the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> can not press its case until appeals are heard involving the Hunts' lawsuit with the Peruvian company <ORGANIZATION> Minpeco </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON>, <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Bunker </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON> and their brother, <PERSON> Lamar </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON>, and others were ordered by a federal court jury in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> to pay Minpeco, the Peruvian governments' silver mining company, $ 134.6 million. The company had lost millions of dollars in the silver price squeeze.
