<HEAD>Sugar Futures Hit New 4-Month High On Brazil Supply Fears</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Sugar futures prices soared to four-month highs Friday on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Coffee, <ORGANIZATION> Sugar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Cocoa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> on expectations of reduced availabilty of sugar from <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, analysts said. On other markets, coffee, cattle, pork, energy and precious-metals futures all gained; grains and soybeans were mixed; and stock-index futures retreated. Sugar for delivery in March settled .55 cent higher at 11.86 cents a pound, the highest daily settlement since Aug. 5, on rumors that the <ORGANIZATION> Brazilian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alcohol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sugar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> was preparing to announce a diversion of substantially more sugar cane from sugar-making to alcohol production. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> has embraced the use of gasohol _ an automobile fuel made from gasoline and alcohol _ like no other country. A recent <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> agreement to limit crude-oil production has pushed oil and gasoline prices higher, which in turn has led to speculation that <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> will renew its efforts to encourage gasohol use, analysts said. If the government-run <ORGANIZATION> Alcohol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sugar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> does indeed announce a greater diversion of sugar cane to alcohol production scheduled for release on Monday, `` obviously that would mean less sugar would be available for exporting purposes,'' said <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevenson </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Sugar prices had fallen earlier in the week on speculation that <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> would soon emerge as a large-volume seller of sugar on the world market. `` This has really turned that situation upside down,'' <PERSON> Stevenson </PERSON> said. Brazilian concerns also fueled a strong rally in the coffee market. It's been a dry spring so far in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, the world's largest coffee producer, and fears of drought damage to the 1988-89 Brazilian coffee crop have begun to surface. Meanwhile, the weather in <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, the No. 2 coffee producer, has been extremely wet, hampering the harvest of the 1987-88 coffee crop, said <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaul </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Coffee settled .29 cent to 1.60 cent higher with March at $ 1.2727 a pound. Livestock and meat futures posted strong gains on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> on bullish signals from the cash markets, including the first signs of a significant drop in hog slaughters since early 1987. Hog kills for the day totaled 337,000 compared to 339,000 a year ago, and kills for the week totaled 1.881 million vs. 1.879 million a year ago. The current figures were closer to year-ago figures than the market has seen in more than a year, and the weekly total was about 3 percent below the previous week, said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Hare </PERSON>, an analyst in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> with <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGAN