<SECOND>AM-Bonds,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bond prices ended mixed in slow trading Friday, reflecting what credit-market strategists called uncertainty over the direction of interest rates. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s 30-year bond rose about -LRB- point or $ 1.25 per $ 1,000 in face amount, and its yield eased to 8.95 percent from 8.96 percent Thursday. One noteworthy development was a rise in rates on short-term <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> notes to yield more than that of 30-year bonds, an unusual shift that last occurred prior to the 1981-82 recession. But the significance of the so-called inverted yield curve remains unclear. Bond strategists said the market was influenced largely by confusion over whether or when the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> will move to tighten credit conditions in order to pre-empt inflationary pressure and keep the dollar stable. They said the confusion may be clarified somewhat next Wednesday, when the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is scheduled to release the market-sensitive monthly trade deficit figures for October. A large imbalance could hurt the dollar's value and force the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> to raise interest rates. In the secondary market for <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bonds, prices of short-term governments fell -LRB- point, intermediate maturities fell \ point and long-term issues rose -LRB- point, the <ORGANIZATION> Telerate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, financial information service reported. The movement of a point equals a change of $ 10 in the price of a bond with a $ 1,000 face value. The <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Bond Index, which measures price movements on all outstanding <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> issues with maturities of a year or longer, fell 1.45 to 1,135.57. In corporate trading, industrials and utilities also fell. <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION>'s Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures price movements on 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, lost 1.00 to 295.10. Prices strengthened slightly in the tax-exempt market. The Bond Buyer index of 40 actively traded municipal bonds was up 7-32 point at 90 as of 3 p.m. EST. The average yield to maturity was 7.90 percent, down from 7.92 percent Thursday. Yields on three-month <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bills fell to 8.14 percent as the discount fell 8 basis points to 7.88 percent. Yields on six-month bills rose to 8.67 percent as the discount rose 4 basis points to 8.21 percent. Yields on one-year bills rose to 8.92 percent as the discount rose 5 basis points to 8.28 percent. A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield is the annualized return on an investment in a <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bill. The discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face value, which is paid at maturity. The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between banks, traded at 8 -LCB- percent, unchanged from late Thursday.
