<DATELINE>NORWALK, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Financial Accounting Standards Board has voted to delay the effective date of its Statement 96, `` Accounting for Income Taxes,'' until fiscal years starting after Dec. 15, 1989. <ORGANIZATION> FASB </ORGANIZATION> project manager <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkens </PERSON> said the board voted to delay the effective date of Statement 96 to allow more time for companies and their auditors to understand how to apply the statement. The board also voted that a new accounting statement, which will be issued later this month, will apply only to companies that have not yet adopted Statement 96. Companies that have already adopted Statement 96 are not permitted to revert to previously applied accounting principles, the board ruled.
</TEXT>
